var documenterSearchIndex = {"docs":
[{"category":"section","location":"africa/#Virtual-plant-simulations-of-Africa","page":"Africa","text":"EcoSISTEM was designed to scale to much larger areas, supporting many more species. As an illustrative example, here we simulate up to 50,000 plant species over Africa at an 80km grid scale, with a constant background environment of 25°C. When all species are given an equal fitness in the habitat, all 50,000 can co-exist over long time scales of over 100 years (Figure 2A). This can be run on a workstation with 24 threads in just under 5 hours.\n\nWe can also explore the behaviour of selective advantage of specialist species over generalists at these scales. When we introduce a specialist species into an African-sized landscape with an existing generalist, the specialist out-competes the generalist and spreads throughout the continent. The larger the selective advantage of the specialist, the faster it is able to invade and colonise across the landscape (Figure 1). These same dynamics can be seen when we introduce a specialist to the full complement of 50,000 species (Figure 1B-D).","title":"Virtual plant simulations of Africa"},{"category":"section","location":"africa/#SINGLE-SPECIES","page":"Africa","text":"using EcoSISTEM\nusing EcoSISTEM.ClimatePref\nusing EcoSISTEM.Units\nusing Unitful\nusing Unitful.DefaultSymbols\nusing Distances\nusing StatsBase\nusing Plots\nfile = pkgdir(EcoSISTEM, \"data\", \"Africa.tif\")\nafrica = readfile(file)\nactive = Matrix{Bool}(.!isnan.(africa))\n\nheatmap(active)\n\n# Set up initial parameters for ecosystem\nnumSpecies = 1; grid = size(africa); demand= 10.0kJ; individuals=0; area = 64e6km^2; totalK = 1000.0kJ/km^2\n\n# Set up how much energy each species consumes\nresource_vec = SolarDemand(fill(demand, numSpecies))\n\n\n# Set rates for birth and death\nbirth = 0.6/year\ndeath = 0.6/year\nlongevity = 1.0\nsurvival = 0.0\nboost = 1.0\n# Collect model parameters together\nparam = EqualPop(birth, death, longevity, survival, boost)\n\n# Create kernel for movement\nkernel = fill(GaussianKernel(15.0km, 10e-10), numSpecies)\nmovement = AlwaysMovement(kernel, Torus())\n\n\n# Create species list, including their temperature preferences, seed abundance and native status\nopts = fill(274.0K, numSpecies)\nvars = fill(0.5K, numSpecies)\ntraits = GaussTrait(opts, vars)\nnative = fill(true, numSpecies)\n# abun = rand(Multinomial(individuals, numSpecies))\nabun = fill(div(individuals, numSpecies), numSpecies)\nsppl = SpeciesList(numSpecies, traits, abun, resource_vec,\n    movement, param, native)\nsppl.params.birth\n\n# Create abiotic environment - even grid of one temperature\nhabitat = simplehabitat(274.0K, grid, totalK, area, active)\n\n\n# Set nichefit between species and environment (gaussian)\nnichefit = Gauss{typeof(1.0K)}()\n\n#Create ecosystem\neco = Ecosystem(sppl, habitat, nichefit)\nrand_start = rand(findall(active), 1)[1]\neco.abundances.grid[1, rand_start[1], rand_start[2]] = 100\n\n# EcoSISTEM Parameters\ntimes = 100years; timestep = 1month; record_interval = 1month; repeats = 1\nlensim = length(0years:record_interval:times)\nabuns = zeros(Int64, numSpecies, prod(grid), lensim)\n@time simulate_record!(abuns, eco, times, record_interval, timestep);\n\nabuns = reshape(abuns[1, :, :, 1], grid[1], grid[2], lensim)\n\nanim = @animate for i in 1:lensim\n    africa_abun = Float64.(abuns[:, :, i])\n    africa_abun[.!(active)] .= NaN\n    heatmap(africa_abun, clim = (0, 700_000), background_color = :lightblue, background_color_outside=:white, grid = false, color = cgrad(:algae, scale = :exp), aspect_ratio = 1)\nend\ngif(anim, \"examples/Biodiversity/Africa.gif\", fps = 30)\n\n#### SPECIALIST VERSUS GENERALIST ####\n\nspecialist_vars = [0.5K, 1.0K, 5.0K, 10.0K, 25.0K, 50.0K]\nvelocity = zeros(typeof(1.0km/month), length(specialist_vars))\nrand_start = rand(findall(active), 1)[1]\nfor i in eachindex(specialist_vars)\n    # Set up initial parameters for ecosystem\n    numSpecies = 2; grid = size(africa); demand= 10.0kJ; individuals=0; area = 64e6km^2; totalK = 1000.0kJ/km^2\n\n    # Set up how much energy each species consumes\n    resource_vec = SolarDemand(fill(demand, numSpecies))\n\n\n    # Set rates for birth and death\n    birth = 0.6/year\n    death = 0.6/year\n    longevity = 1.0\n    survival = 0.1\n    boost = 1.0\n    # Collect model parameters together\n    param = EqualPop(birth, death, longevity, survival, boost)\n\n    # Create kernel for movement\n    kernel = fill(GaussianKernel(15.0km, 10e-10), numSpecies)\n    movement = AlwaysMovement(kernel, Torus())\n\n\n    # Create species list, including their temperature preferences, seed abundance and native status\n    opts = fill(274.0K, numSpecies)\n    vars = [50.0K, specialist_vars[i]]\n    traits = GaussTrait(opts, vars)\n    native = fill(true, numSpecies)\n    # abun = rand(Multinomial(individuals, numSpecies))\n    abun = fill(div(individuals, numSpecies), numSpecies)\n    sppl = SpeciesList(numSpecies, traits, abun, resource_vec,\n        movement, param, native)\n    sppl.params.birth\n\n    # Create abiotic environment - even grid of one temperature\n    habitat = simplehabitat(274.0K, grid, totalK, area, active)\n\n    # Set nichefit between species and environment (gaussian)\n    nichefit = Gauss{typeof(1.0K)}()\n\n    #Create ecosystem\n    eco = Ecosystem(sppl, habitat, nichefit)\n    eco.abundances.grid[1, rand_start[1], rand_start[2]] = 100\n\n    # EcoSISTEM Parameters\n    burnin = 100years; times = 100years; timestep = 1month; record_interval = 1month; repeats = 1\n    lensim = length(0years:record_interval:times)\n    simulate!(eco, burnin,timestep)\n    eco.abundances.grid[2, rand_start[1], rand_start[2]] = 100\n    abuns = zeros(Int64, numSpecies, prod(grid), lensim)\n    @time simulate_record!(abuns, eco, times, record_interval, timestep);\n\n    abuns = reshape(abuns[:, :, :, 1], numSpecies, grid[1], grid[2], lensim)\n    origin = [rand_start[1], rand_start[2]]\n    dest = findall(abuns[2, :, :, 1] .> 0)\n    inst_velocity = map(1:lensim) do t\n        dest = findall(abuns[2, :, :, t] .> 0)\n        dists = [euclidean(origin, [dest[i][1], dest[i][2]]) for i in eachindex(dest)] .* getgridsize(eco)\n        return maximum(dists)/month\n    end\n    velocity[i] = mean(inst_velocity)\nend\n\nplot(ustrip.(abs.(specialist_vars .- 50.0K)), ustrip.(velocity),\n    xlab = \"Selective advantage\", ylab = \"Invasion speed (km/month)\",\n    label = \"\", grid = false)\n\n(Image: ) Figure 1: Invasive capacity of a specialist plant species versus a generalist. Selective advantage is the difference in niche width between the specialist and generalist, and invasion speed is calculated as the average distance travelled per month by the specialist.","title":"SINGLE SPECIES"},{"category":"section","location":"africa/#ONE-SPECIALIST-VERSUS-MANY-GENERALISTS","page":"Africa","text":"using EcoSISTEM\nusing EcoSISTEM.ClimatePref\nusing EcoSISTEM.Units\nusing Unitful\nusing Unitful.DefaultSymbols\nusing JLD2\nusing Printf\nfile = pkgdir(EcoSISTEM, \"data\", \"Africa.tif\")\nafrica = readfile(file)\nactive = Matrix{Bool}(.!isnan.(africa))\n# Set up initial parameters for ecosystem\nnumSpecies = 50_000; grid = size(africa); demand= 10.0kJ; individuals=3*10^8; area = 64e6km^2; totalK = 1000.0kJ/km^2\n\n# Set up how much energy each species consumes\nresource_vec = SolarDemand(fill(demand, numSpecies))\n\n\n# Set rates for birth and death\nbirth = 0.6/year\ndeath = 0.6/year\nlongevity = 1.0\nsurvival = 0.1\nboost = 1.0\n# Collect model parameters together\nparam = EqualPop(birth, death, longevity, survival, boost)\n\n# Create kernel for movement\nkernel = fill(GaussianKernel(15.0km, 10e-10), numSpecies)\nmovement = AlwaysMovement(kernel, Torus())\n\n\n# Create species list, including their temperature preferences, seed abundance and native status\nopts = fill(274.0K, numSpecies)\nvars = fill(50.0K, numSpecies)\nvars[50_000] = 0.5K\ntraits = GaussTrait(opts, vars)\nnative = fill(true, numSpecies)\n# abun = rand(Multinomial(individuals, numSpecies))\nabun = fill(div(individuals, numSpecies), numSpecies)\nsppl = SpeciesList(numSpecies, traits, abun, resource_vec,\n    movement, param, native)\nsppl.params.birth\n\n# Create abiotic environment - even grid of one temperature\nhabitat = simplehabitat(274.0K, grid, totalK, area, active)\n\n\n# Set nichefit between species and environment (gaussian)\nnichefit = Gauss{typeof(1.0K)}()\n\n#Create ecosystem\neco = Ecosystem(sppl, habitat, nichefit)\neco.abundances.matrix[50_000, :] .= 0\n\nimport EcoSISTEM.simulate!\nfunction simulate!(eco::Ecosystem, times::Unitful.Time, timestep::Unitful.Time, cacheInterval::Unitful.Time, cacheFolder::String, scenario_name::String)\n  time_seq = 0s:timestep:times\n  counting = 0\n  for i in eachindex(time_seq)\n      update!(eco, timestep);\n      # Save cache of abundances\n      if mod(time_seq[i], cacheInterval) == 0year\n          @save (joinpath(cacheFolder, scenario_name * (@sprintf \"%02d.jld2\" uconvert(NoUnits,time_seq[i]/cacheInterval))) abun = eco.abundances.matrix\n      end\n  end\nend\n\n# EcoSISTEM Parameters\nburnin = 100years; times = 100years; timestep = 1month; record_interval = 12months;\nlensim = length(0years:record_interval:times)\n@time simulate!(eco, burnin, timestep)\nrand_start = rand(findall(active), 1)[1]\neco.abundances.grid[50_000, rand_start[1], rand_start[2]] = 100\n@time simulate!(eco, times, timestep, record_interval, \"examples/Biodiversity\", \"Africa_run\");","title":"ONE SPECIALIST VERSUS MANY GENERALISTS"},{"category":"section","location":"africa/#50,000-SPECIES-COEXISTING","page":"Africa","text":"using EcoSISTEM\nusing EcoSISTEM.ClimatePref\nusing EcoSISTEM.Units\nusing Unitful\nusing Unitful.DefaultSymbols\nusing JLD2\nusing Printf\n\nfile = pkgdir(EcoSISTEM, \"data\", \"Africa.tif\")\nafrica = readfile(file)\nactive = Matrix{Bool}(.!isnan.(africa))\n# Set up initial parameters for ecosystem\nnumSpecies = 50_000; grid = size(africa); demand= 10.0kJ; individuals=3*10^8; area = 64e6km^2; totalK = 1000.0kJ/km^2\n\n# Set up how much energy each species consumes\nresource_vec = SolarDemand(fill(demand, numSpecies))\n\n\n# Set rates for birth and death\nbirth = 0.6/year\ndeath = 0.6/year\nlongevity = 1.0\nsurvival = 0.1\nboost = 1.0\n# Collect model parameters together\nparam = EqualPop(birth, death, longevity, survival, boost)\n\n# Create kernel for movement\nkernel = fill(GaussianKernel(15.0km, 10e-10), numSpecies)\nmovement = AlwaysMovement(kernel, Torus())\n\n\n# Create species list, including their temperature preferences, seed abundance and native status\nopts = fill(274.0K, numSpecies)\nvars = fill(50.0K, numSpecies)\ntraits = GaussTrait(opts, vars)\nnative = fill(true, numSpecies)\n# abun = rand(Multinomial(individuals, numSpecies))\nabun = fill(div(individuals, numSpecies), numSpecies)\nsppl = SpeciesList(numSpecies, traits, abun, resource_vec,\n    movement, param, native)\nsppl.params.birth\n\n# Create abiotic environment - even grid of one temperature\nhabitat = simplehabitat(274.0K, grid, totalK, area, active)\n\n\n# Set nichefit between species and environment (gaussian)\nnichefit = Gauss{typeof(1.0K)}()\n\n#Create ecosystem\neco = Ecosystem(sppl, habitat, nichefit)\n\n# EcoSISTEM Parameters\nburnin = 10years; times = 100years; timestep = 1month; record_interval = 12months;\nlensim = length(0years:record_interval:times)\n@time simulate!(eco, burnin, timestep)\n@time simulate!(eco, times, timestep, record_interval, \"examples/Biodiversity\", \"Africa_run_coexist\");\n\nusing JLD2\nusing Plots\nusing Diversity\nabuns = @load \"examples/Biodiversity/Africa_run_coexist100.jld2\" abun\nmeta = Metacommunity(abuns)\ndiv = norm_sub_alpha(meta, 0)\nsumabuns = reshape(div[!, :diversity], 100, 100)\nheatmap(sumabuns,\n    background_color = :lightblue,\n    background_color_outside=:white,\n    grid = false, color = :algae,\n    aspect_ratio = 1, layout = (@layout [a b; c d]),\n    clim = (0, 50_000), margin = 0.5 * Plots.mm,\n    title = \"A\", titleloc = :left)\n\nabuns = @load \"examples/Biodiversity/Africa_run50.jld2\" abun\nmeta = Metacommunity(abuns)\ndiv = norm_sub_alpha(meta, 0)\nsumabuns = reshape(div[!, :diversity], 100, 100)\nheatmap!(sumabuns,\n    background_color = :lightblue,\n    background_color_outside=:white,\n    grid = false, color = :algae,\n    aspect_ratio = 1, subplot = 2,\n    clim = (0, 50_000), right_margin = 2.0 * Plots.mm,\n    title = \"B\", titleloc = :left)\n\nabuns = @load \"examples/Biodiversity/Africa_run100.jld2\" abun\nmeta = Metacommunity(abuns)\ndiv = norm_sub_alpha(meta, 0)\nsumabuns = reshape(div[!, :diversity], 100, 100)\nheatmap!(sumabuns,\n    background_color = :lightblue,\n    background_color_outside=:white,\n    grid = false, color = :algae,\n    aspect_ratio = 1, subplot = 3,\n    clim = (0, 50_000), right_margin = 2.0 * Plots.mm,\n    title = \"C\", titleloc = :left)\n\n\nabuns = @load \"examples/Biodiversity/Africa_run50.jld2\" abun\nmeta = Metacommunity(abuns)\ndiv = norm_sub_rho(meta, 1.0)\nsumabuns = reshape(div[!, :diversity], 100, 100)\nheatmap!(sumabuns,\n    background_color = :lightblue,\n    background_color_outside=:white,\n    grid = false, color = :algae,\n    aspect_ratio = 1, subplot = 4,\n     right_margin = 2.0 * Plots.mm,\n    title = \"D\", titleloc = :left, clim = (0, 1))\n\n(Image: ) Figure 2: 100 year simulations of Africa with 50,000 species. (A) Species richness after 100 years of simulation with all species equal. (B) Species richness after 50 years, with one specialist introduced. (C) Species richness after 100 years, with one specialist introduced. (D) Representativeness after 50 years with one specialist introduced (0 is completely unrepresentative of the ecosystem as a whole, 1 is completely representative).","title":"50,000 SPECIES COEXISTING"},{"category":"section","location":"api/#API","page":"API","text":"\n\n","title":"API"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.AbstractDemand","page":"API","text":"Abstract1Demand{R}\n\nAbstract supertype for all species resource demand types, parameterised by the type(s) of resource required R.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.AbstractDemand"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.AbstractEcosystem","page":"API","text":"AbstractEcosystem{Part <: AbstractHabitat, SL <: SpeciesList,\n    NF <: AbstractNicheFit} <: AbstractMetacommunity{Float64,\n        Matrix{Int64}, Matrix{Float64}, SL, Part}\n\nAbstract supertype for all ecosystem types and a subtype of AbstractMetacommunity.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.AbstractEcosystem"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.AbstractHabitat","page":"API","text":"AbstractHabitat{H <: AbstractRegime, B <: AbstractSupply} <: AbstractPartition\n\nAbstract supertype for all abiotic environment types and a subtype of AbstractPartition\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.AbstractHabitat"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.AbstractLayer","page":"API","text":"AbstractLayer{R <: Role}\n\nAbstract supertype of the materialised, hot-loop grid layers, tagged with their Role (Condition condition or Resource resource). Concrete kinds are ContinuousLayer, DiscreteLayer and the collections LayerCollection2/LayerCollection3.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.AbstractLayer"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.AbstractMovement","page":"API","text":"AbstractMovement\n\nAbstract supertype of movements\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.AbstractMovement"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.AbstractNicheFit","page":"API","text":"AbstractNicheFit{NF}\n\nThe abstract supertype of relationships between a trait and its environment, parameterised on any NF.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.AbstractNicheFit"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.AbstractParams","page":"API","text":"AbstractParams\n\nAbstract supertype for all simulation parameter types\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.AbstractParams"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.AbstractRegime","page":"API","text":"AbstractRegime\n\nAn environmental condition matched to species tolerances — any Condition-role AbstractLayer.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.AbstractRegime"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.AbstractScenario","page":"API","text":"AbstractScenario\n\nAbstract supertype for all whole ecosystem change scenarios\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.AbstractScenario"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.AbstractSupply","page":"API","text":"AbstractSupply\n\nA resource layer consumed by species — any Resource-role AbstractLayer.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.AbstractSupply"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.AbstractTolerance","page":"API","text":"AbstractTolerance{T}\n\nAbstract supertype for all tolerance types, parameterised by their response type of any type T.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.AbstractTolerance"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.Altitude","page":"API","text":"Altitude <: NicheAxis — elevation above sea level (WorldClim Elevation; m).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.Altitude"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.AlwaysMovement","page":"API","text":"AlwaysMovement{K <: AbstractKernel, B <: BoundaryCondition} <: AbstractMovement\n\nMovement can happen to any individual (\"animal-like\").\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.AlwaysMovement"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.AlwaysMovement-Tuple{Vector{K} where K<:EcoSISTEM.AbstractKernel}","page":"API","text":"AlwaysMovement{K <: AbstractKernel, B <: BoundaryCondition} <: AbstractMovement\n\nMovement can happen to any individual (\"animal-like\").\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.AlwaysMovement"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.BirthOnlyMovement","page":"API","text":"BirthOnlyMovement{K <: AbstractKernel, B <: BoundaryCondition} <: AbstractMovement\n\nMovement can only happen to individuals that have just been born (\"plant-like\").\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.BirthOnlyMovement"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.BirthOnlyMovement-Tuple{Vector{K} where K<:EcoSISTEM.AbstractKernel}","page":"API","text":"BirthOnlyMovement{K <: AbstractKernel, B <: BoundaryCondition} <: AbstractMovement\n\nMovement can only happen to individuals that have just been born (\"plant-like\").\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.BirthOnlyMovement"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.BoundaryCondition","page":"API","text":"BoundaryCondition\n\nAn abstract type for what should happen at the boundaries of an ecosystem.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.BoundaryCondition"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.Cache","page":"API","text":"Cache\n\nCache houses an integer array of moves made by all species in a timestep for the update! function, netmigration.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.Cache"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.CachedEcosystem","page":"API","text":"CachedEcosystem{Part <: AbstractHabitat, SL <: SpeciesList,\n    NF <: AbstractNicheFit} <: AbstractEcosystem{Part, SL, NF}\n\nCachedEcosystem houses the same information as Ecosystem (see ?Ecosystem), but holds the time period abundances as a CachedGridLandscape, so that they may be present or missing.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.CachedEcosystem"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.CachedEcosystem-Tuple{Ecosystem, String, StepRangeLen}","page":"API","text":"CachedEcosystem(eco::Ecosystem, outputfile::String, times::StepRangeLen;\n                saveinterval::Unitful.Time = step(times))\n\nCreate a CachedEcosystem given an existing Ecosystem, eco, an output folder to which the simulations are saved, outputfile, and a range of times over which to simulate, times. The step of times is the simulation timestep; saveinterval controls how often checkpoints are written to disk (a multiple of the timestep, defaulting to every step). Because the simulation always advances by the timestep, results are independent of saveinterval.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.CachedEcosystem"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.CachedGridLandscape","page":"API","text":"CachedGridLandscape\n\nEcosystem abundances for a cached simulation. matrix is an AxisArray over time where each slot holds either a GridLandscape or missing. outputfolder is the path to the folder where JLD2 cache files are written. timestep is the simulation step (the granularity of the time axis) and saveinterval is the (possibly coarser) interval at which checkpoints are written to disk; it must be a multiple of timestep. Because the simulation always advances by timestep, the results are independent of saveinterval.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.CachedGridLandscape"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.CachedGridLandscape-Tuple{String, StepRangeLen}","page":"API","text":"CachedGridLandscape(file::String, times::StepRangeLen;\n                    saveinterval::Unitful.Time = step(times))\n\nConstruct a CachedGridLandscape backed by the folder file, initialising all timepoints in the range times to missing. The simulation timestep is the step size of times; saveinterval sets how often checkpoints are written to disk and must be a multiple of the timestep (it defaults to saving every step).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.CachedGridLandscape"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.CarbonAxis","page":"API","text":"CarbonAxis <: NicheAxis — carbon-cycle niche axes.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.CarbonAxis"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.CarbonFlux","page":"API","text":"CarbonFlux <: CarbonAxis — net primary productivity, a carbon flux (BioClimPlus npp; g·m⁻²·year⁻¹).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.CarbonFlux"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.ClimateMoisture","page":"API","text":"ClimateMoisture <: ClimateMoistureAxis — climate moisture index, precipitation minus potential evapotranspiration (Climate cmi, BioClimPlus cmi_max/mean/min; kg·m⁻²·month⁻¹).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.ClimateMoisture"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.ClimateMoistureAxis","page":"API","text":"ClimateMoistureAxis <: WaterAxis — climate-moisture-index niche axes (level and range).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.ClimateMoistureAxis"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.ClimateMoistureRange","page":"API","text":"ClimateMoistureRange <: ClimateMoistureAxis — annual range of the monthly climate moisture index (BioClimPlus cmi_range; kg·m⁻²·month⁻¹).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.ClimateMoistureRange"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.ClimateTypology","page":"API","text":"ClimateTypology <: TypologyAxis — categorical climate-classification classes (BioClimPlus kg0-5: Köppen-Geiger, Wissmann, Thornthwaite, Troll-Pfaffen).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.ClimateTypology"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.CloudCover","page":"API","text":"CloudCover <: CloudCoverAxis — total cloud cover (Climate clt, BioClimPlus clt_max/mean/min; dimensionless).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.CloudCover"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.CloudCoverAxis","page":"API","text":"CloudCoverAxis <: NicheAxis — cloud-cover niche axes (level and range).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.CloudCoverAxis"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.CloudCoverRange","page":"API","text":"CloudCoverRange <: CloudCoverAxis — annual range of the monthly total cloud cover (BioClimPlus clt_range; dimensionless).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.CloudCoverRange"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.Condition","page":"API","text":"Condition <: Role\n\nMarker for a layer used as an environmental condition (matched to species tolerances).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.Condition"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.ContinuousLayer","page":"API","text":"ContinuousLayer{R <: Role, A <: NicheAxis, V <: Number, Arr <: AbstractArray{V}}\n\nA continuous (numeric) grid layer of role R on niche axis A, holding a value matrix (eltype V). The array type Arr carries the rank: a Matrix{V} is a static layer (time unused, = 1), an AbstractArray{V, 3} a monthly time series indexed by time.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.ContinuousLayer"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.ContinuousRegime","page":"API","text":"ContinuousRegime{C} — a static continuous regime (a `Condition`-role [`ContinuousLayer`](@ref) over a `Matrix{C}`).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.ContinuousRegime"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.ContinuousTimeRegime","page":"API","text":"ContinuousTimeRegime{C, M} — a monthly time-varying continuous regime (a `Condition`-role [`ContinuousLayer`](@ref) over a 3-D array).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.ContinuousTimeRegime"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.ContinuousTolerance","page":"API","text":"ContinuousTolerance{C <: Number} <: AbstractTolerance{T}\n\nAbstract trait type that holds information on a single continuous trait for each species, of any Number type C.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.ContinuousTolerance"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.CumulativeHeat","page":"API","text":"CumulativeHeat <: TemperatureAxis — accumulated growing degree-days above a threshold (BioClimPlus gdd0/gdd5/gdd10; K·day).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.CumulativeHeat"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.Cylinder","page":"API","text":"Cylinder <: BoundaryCondition\n\nA cylindrical boundary where species can cross the x boundary but not the y.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.Cylinder"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.DayAxis","page":"API","text":"DayAxis <: NicheAxis — day-based phenology niche axes (day-of-year positions and day counts; day).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.DayAxis"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.DayOfYear","page":"API","text":"DayOfYear <: DayAxis — an ordinal day-of-year: first/last growing day or first/last day above a degree-day threshold (BioClimPlus fgd/lgd/gdgfgd*/gddlgd*; day).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.DayOfYear"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.DayRange","page":"API","text":"DayRange <: DayAxis — a count or span of days: growing-season length, snow-cover days or number of days above a threshold (BioClimPlus gsl/scd/ngd*; day).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.DayRange"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.DemandCollection2","page":"API","text":"DemandCollection2{R1, R2}\n\nA pair of species resource demands (e.g. solar resource and water) consumed together, to match a two-resource supply.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.DemandCollection2"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.DiscreteLayer","page":"API","text":"DiscreteLayer{A <: NicheAxis, V, Arr <: AbstractArray{V}}\n\nA discrete (categorical) grid layer on niche axis A — always a Condition (there is no discrete supply).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.DiscreteLayer"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.DiscreteRegime","page":"API","text":"DiscreteRegime{D} — a categorical regime (a [`DiscreteLayer`](@ref), e.g. land cover).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.DiscreteRegime"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.DiscreteTolerance","page":"API","text":"BasicTrait{T} <: AbstractTolerance{T}\n\nBasic trait type that holds information on a single trait for each species, of any type T.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.DiscreteTolerance"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.DiversitySet-Union{Tuple{T}, Tuple{CachedEcosystem, Vector{T}}} where T<:(Union{Unitful.Quantity{T, 𝐓, U}, Unitful.Level{L, S, Unitful.Quantity{T, 𝐓, U}} where {L, S}} where {T, U})","page":"API","text":"DiversitySet(cache::CachedEcosystem, times::Vector{T}) where T <: Unitful.Time\n\nConstruct a DiversitySet from a CachedEcosystem, initialising it with the cache output folder and a vector of timepoints times for which diversity is to be recorded.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.DiversitySet"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.Ecosystem","page":"API","text":"Ecosystem{Part <: AbstractHabitat} <:\n   AbstractEcosystem{Part, SL, NF}\n\nEcosystem houses information on species and their interaction with their environment. For species, it holds abundances and locations, as well as properties such as trait information, spplist, and movement types, lookup. For environments, it provides information on environmental conditions and available resources,habitat. Finally, there is a slot for the nichefit between the environment and the characteristics of the species, nichefit.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.Ecosystem"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.Ecosystem-Tuple{SpeciesList, GridHabitat, EcoSISTEM.AbstractNicheFit}","page":"API","text":"```julia\nEcosystem{Part <: AbstractHabitat} <:\n   AbstractEcosystem{Part, SL, NF}\n```\n\nEcosystem houses information on species and their interaction with their environment. For species, it holds abundances and locations, as well as properties such as trait information, `spplist`, and movement types, `lookup`. For environments, it provides information on environmental conditions and available resources,`habitat`. Finally, there is a slot for the nichefit between the environment and the characteristics of the species, `nichefit`.\n\n\n```julia\nEcosystem(spplist::SpeciesList, habitat::GridHabitat,\n    nichefit::AbstractNicheFit)\n```\n\nCreate an `Ecosystem` given a species list, an abiotic environment and trait nichefit. An optional population function can be added, `popfun`, which defaults to generic random filling of the ecosystem. A `seed` may be supplied to make the run reproducible: it deterministically seeds one random number generator per species (see [`makerngs`](@ref)), so results are identical regardless of the number of threads used. If no `seed` is given, one is drawn at random.\n\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.Ecosystem"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.Ecosystem-Union{Tuple{DM}, Tuple{T}, Tuple{F}, Tuple{F, SpeciesList{T, DM}, GridHabitat, EcoSISTEM.AbstractNicheFit}} where {F<:Function, T, DM}","page":"API","text":"Ecosystem(spplist::SpeciesList, habitat::GridHabitat,\n    nichefit::AbstractNicheFit)\n\nCreate an Ecosystem given a species list, an abiotic environment and trait nichefit. An optional population function can be added, popfun, which defaults to generic random filling of the ecosystem. A seed may be supplied to make the run reproducible: it deterministically seeds one random number generator per species (see makerngs), so results are identical regardless of the number of threads used. If no seed is given, one is drawn at random.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.Ecosystem"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.EqualPop","page":"API","text":"EqualPop <: AbstractParams\n\nParameter type that holds information on a population's birth and death rates, birth and death, specifically populations where all species have the same information. l represents the longevity of species based on their resource demands and s is the survival of species dependent on how well their tolerances reflect the environment. Finally boost is used to manipulate how much of a boost the species get from being in an environment with lots of available resource.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.EqualPop"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.Evapotranspiration","page":"API","text":"Evapotranspiration <: EvapotranspirationAxis — potential evapotranspiration (Climate pet, BioClimPlus pet_penman_max/mean/min; kg·m⁻²·month⁻¹).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.Evapotranspiration"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.EvapotranspirationAxis","page":"API","text":"EvapotranspirationAxis <: WaterAxis — evapotranspiration niche axes (level and range).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.EvapotranspirationAxis"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.EvapotranspirationRange","page":"API","text":"EvapotranspirationRange <: EvapotranspirationAxis — annual range of the monthly potential evapotranspiration (BioClimPlus pet_penman_range; kg·m⁻²·month⁻¹).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.EvapotranspirationRange"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.FluctScenario","page":"API","text":"FluctScenario <: AbstractScenario\n\nScenario type that fluctuates the environment periodically. fun is the fluctuation function, rate is the rate of temperature change, and startarray holds the baseline regime values at the start of the simulation.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.FluctScenario"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.FrostChangeFrequency","page":"API","text":"FrostChangeFrequency <: TemperatureAxis — frost change frequency, the number of days the temperature crosses 0 °C (BioClimPlus fcf; dimensionless).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.FrostChangeFrequency"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.Gauss","page":"API","text":"Gauss{NF} <: AbstractNicheFit{NF}\n\nwarning: Deprecated\nGauss is deprecated and will be removed; use NicheSuitability instead (a Gaussian preference is the Normal case of a NicheTolerance). This shim shares NicheSuitability's 2-argument density functor and also retains the legacy 3-argument (current, opt, sd) Gaussian call for back-compatibility.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.Gauss"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.GaussianKernel","page":"API","text":"GaussianKernel <: AbstractKernel\n\nGaussianMovement holds parameters for a gaussian movement kernel; a dispersal variance for a species, var, and a threshold, thresh, beyond which dispersal cannot take place.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.GaussianKernel"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.GridHabitat","page":"API","text":"GridHabitat{H, B} <: AbstractHabitat{H, B}\n\nAbiotic environment type holding a regime of type H, a boolean active matrix indicating which grid cells are accessible, a supply of type B representing available resources, and a vector of names for each subcommunity.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.GridHabitat"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.GridLandscape","page":"API","text":"GridLandscape\n\nEcosystem abundances housed in the landscape. matrix stores abundances as a 2-dimensional array (species × grid cells) for computational efficiency, and grid is a 3-dimensional view of the same data (species × x × y). Random draws during simulation use Julia's task-local default RNG, so no generator state is stored here.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.GridLandscape"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.GridLandscape-Tuple{EcoSISTEM.SavedLandscape, Tuple}","page":"API","text":"GridLandscape(sl::SavedLandscape, dimension::Tuple)\n\nRestore a GridLandscape from a SavedLandscape, reshaping the abundance matrix to dimension. The saved RNG snapshot is restored separately at the load site (see loadfile).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.GridLandscape"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.GrowingSeasonPrecipitation","page":"API","text":"GrowingSeasonPrecipitation <: WaterAxis — precipitation accumulated over the growing season (BioClimPlus gsp; kg·m⁻²).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.GrowingSeasonPrecipitation"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.Heterogeneity","page":"API","text":"Heterogeneity <: NicheAxis — spatial habitat-heterogeneity metrics of EVI (EarthEnv HabitatHeterogeneity; dimensionless).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.Heterogeneity"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.HumidityAxis","page":"API","text":"HumidityAxis <: WaterAxis — atmospheric-water niche axes (vapour pressure, its deficit, relative humidity).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.HumidityAxis"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.Isothermality","page":"API","text":"Isothermality <: TemperatureAxis — isothermality, 100 × (mean diurnal range / annual range) (BioClim 3; dimensionless).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.Isothermality"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.LandCoverTypology","page":"API","text":"LandCoverTypology <: TypologyAxis — categorical land-cover / land-use classes (EarthEnv LandCover 1-12).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.LandCoverTypology"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.LatLong","page":"API","text":"LatLong(lat, long)\nLatLong(; lat, long)\n\nA geographic location or region in Unitful degrees, validated on construction. Pass two angles for a point (LatLong(50.0°, -3.0°)), or two ° intervals for a bounding box (LatLong(54.6°..58.7°, -6.2°.. -1.8°)). Latitude must lie in [-90°, 90°] and longitude in (-180°, 180°] — for a box, both endpoints, and neither interval may be reversed.\n\nThe fields .lat and .long hold the latitude and longitude (each a scalar or an interval), so a LatLong is a drop-in replacement for the old (lat = …, long = …) coordinate/cut/region NamedTuples. A point implements the GeoInterface PointTrait (with the usual X = longitude, Y = latitude order, stripped to plain degrees); a box implements Extents.extent.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.LatLong"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.LayerCollection2","page":"API","text":"LayerCollection2{R <: Role, L1, L2}\nLayerCollection3{R <: Role, L1, L2, L3}\n\nA collection of 2 or 3 layers of the same role R over one grid (e.g. temperature + rainfall). Sub-layer types are kept concrete in named fields for hot-loop type stability.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.LayerCollection2"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.LayerUpdate","page":"API","text":"LayerUpdate{F <: Function, DT}\n\nStores the update rule for a layer. changefun is applied to the layer matrix at each timestep, and rate is the rate of change with appropriate units.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.LayerUpdate"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.LayerUpdate-Union{Tuple{D}, Tuple{DT}, Tuple{F}, Tuple{F, DT, Type{D}}} where {F<:Function, DT, D<:Unitful.Dimensions}","page":"API","text":"LayerUpdate(changefun::F, rate::DT, ::Type{D})\n\nConstruct a LayerUpdate with a type-checked rate. Errors if rate * 1month does not have dimensions D.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.LayerUpdate"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.LongTailKernel","page":"API","text":"LongTailKernel <: AbstractKernel\n\nLongTailKernel holds parameters for a movement kernel; a dispersal variance for a species, var, and a threshold, thresh, beyond which dispersal cannot take place.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.LongTailKernel"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.Lookup","page":"API","text":"Lookup\n\nLookup houses information on x, y grid locations and the probability of occurrence at the location for the species in question p. pnew and moves are initially empty storage and written over by the movement step in update!(). pnew is the recalculated probability based on which directions are available and moves is the number of moves to that grid location in that step.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.Lookup"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.MatchSuitability","page":"API","text":"MatchSuitability{NF} <: AbstractNicheFit{NF}\n\nThe nichefit between a discrete trait and its environment, paramaterised on any NF. Current conditions are matched to a trait preference and checked for a match.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.MatchSuitability"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.MultiScenario","page":"API","text":"MultiScenario{S1 <: AbstractScenario, S2 <: AbstractScenario} <: AbstractScenario\n\nScenario type that composes two scenarios, applying sc1 and then sc2 in sequence at each timestep.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.MultiScenario"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.NicheAxis","page":"API","text":"NicheAxis\n\nAbstract supertype of the niche-axis markers naming what a layer measures (e.g. Temperature, Precipitation), independent of its unit and orthogonal to Role. Extend it with your own struct MyAxis <: NicheAxis end. Related axes are grouped under an abstract intermediate named …Axis (TemperatureAxis, WaterAxis) that carries their shared interface.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.NicheAxis"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.NicheSuitability","page":"API","text":"NicheSuitability{NF} <: AbstractNicheFit{NF}\n\nThe nichefit between a NicheTolerance continuous trait and its environment: the density of the trait's response distribution evaluated at the current regime value, parameterised on any NF. Works for any Distributions.ContinuousUnivariateDistribution (e.g. Trapezoid or Uniform).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.NicheSuitability"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.NicheTolerance","page":"API","text":"NicheTolerance{A <: NicheAxis, C, D} <: ContinuousTolerance{C}\n\nTrait type holding a binned regime preference for each species on niche axis A, as one built continuous response distribution per species — dists::Vector{D}, where D is a concrete Distributions.ContinuousUnivariateDistribution (e.g. Trapezoid{Float64} or Uniform{Float64}). The distributions are built once in the support frame C — the unit their support/domain is measured in, which is also the trait's eltype and the unit the matching regime must be in. In the hot loop the NicheSuitability nichefit fetches dists[sp] — see getdist — and evaluates the density at ustrip(regime), already a bare number in frame C, so there is no per-call conversion or allocation.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.NicheTolerance"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.NicheTolerance-Union{Tuple{D}, Tuple{A}, Tuple{Type{A}, Type{D}, Matrix}} where {A<:NicheAxis, D}","page":"API","text":"NicheTolerance(::Type{A}, ::Type{D}, dist::Matrix; support = canonicalunit(A()),\n    offset = nothing, scale = nothing, probes = …)\n\nBuild a NicheTolerance on axis A with response distribution D from a bare parameter matrix (one species per row). support is the frame the distribution is built in — the unit its support/domain is measured in, the trait's eltype, and the unit the matching regime must be in (defaults to the axis's canonical unit). The bare numbers are taken to be in that frame. offset/scale (references in support) place a shape-only distribution (Beta, LogNormal, …) on the dimensioned axis via a LocationScale.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.NicheTolerance"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.NicheTolerance-Union{Tuple{D}, Tuple{A}, Tuple{Type{A}, Type{D}, Vararg{AbstractVector}}} where {A<:NicheAxis, D}","page":"API","text":"NicheTolerance(::Type{A}, ::Type{D}, params::AbstractVector...; support = canonicalunit(A()),\n    offset = nothing, scale = nothing, probes = …)\n\nBuild a NicheTolerance on axis A with response distribution D from one (unitful) vector per parameter of D — the ergonomic, programmatic counterpart of the dist::Matrix constructor (and of the old GaussTrait(A, mean, sd)). Each params vector holds one distribution parameter across species, e.g. NicheTolerance(Temperature, Normal, opts, vars) (a μ and a σ vector) or NicheTolerance(Precipitation, Gamma, shape, scale_vec). The vectors' own units are respected (read per role); the distribution is built in the support frame (the unit its support/domain — and the matching regime — is measured in, default canonical), converting the inputs to it. So support = K and support = °C build the same preference in the K and °C frames respectively (pdf(getdist(bin, sp), ustrip(support, x)) is correct in each); the frame is the trait's eltype, and a NicheTolerance only matches a regime in that same unit. All parameter vectors must share a unit (a mixed set errors) and have one entry per species.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.NicheTolerance"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.NoBoundary","page":"API","text":"NoBoundary <: BoundaryCondition\n\nA hard boundary where no species can cross.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.NoBoundary"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.NoFitContinuous","page":"API","text":"NoFitContinuous{NF} <: AbstractNicheFit{NF}\n\nThe absence of a nichefit between a continuous trait and its environment, paramaterised on any NF. Returns the value 1.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.NoFitContinuous"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.NoFitDiscrete","page":"API","text":"NoFitDiscrete{NF} <: AbstractNicheFit{NF}\n\nThe absence of a nichefit between a discrete trait and its environment, paramaterised on any NF. Returns the value 1.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.NoFitDiscrete"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.NoMovement","page":"API","text":"NoMovement{K <: AbstractKernel, B <: BoundaryCondition} <: AbstractMovement\n\nNo movement can take place.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.NoMovement"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.PopGrowth","page":"API","text":"PopGrowth <: AbstractParams\n\nBasic parameter type that holds information on a population's birth and death rates, birth and death, as well as how these are altered by resource availability. l represents the longevity of species based on their resource demands and s is the survival of species dependent on how well their tolerances reflect the environment.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.PopGrowth"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.Precipitation","page":"API","text":"Precipitation <: PrecipitationAxis — a precipitation amount over a month, quarter or year (BioClim 12-19, Climate prec/pr; mm). Carries the `mm` unit and provides a water supply/demand.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.Precipitation"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.PrecipitationAxis","page":"API","text":"PrecipitationAxis <: WaterAxis — precipitation niche axes. A topical group; the `mm` unit and the water supply/demand live on the [`Precipitation`](@ref) leaf.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.PrecipitationAxis"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.PrecipitationSeasonality","page":"API","text":"PrecipitationSeasonality <: PrecipitationAxis — precipitation seasonality, the coefficient of variation of the monthly precipitation totals (BioClim 15; dimensionless).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.PrecipitationSeasonality"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.RainTolerance","page":"API","text":"RainTolerance — a binned rainfall preference (a [`NicheTolerance`](@ref) on `Precipitation`, mm frame, with a `Uniform` response).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.RainTolerance"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.RegimeCollection2","page":"API","text":"RegimeCollection2{H1, H2} — two regimes over one grid (e.g. temperature + rainfall).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.RegimeCollection2"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.RegimeCollection3","page":"API","text":"RegimeCollection3{H1, H2, H3} — three regimes over one grid.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.RegimeCollection3"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.RelativeHumidity","page":"API","text":"RelativeHumidity <: RelativeHumidityAxis — near-surface relative humidity (Climate hurs, BioClimPlus hurs_max/mean/min; dimensionless).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.RelativeHumidity"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.RelativeHumidityAxis","page":"API","text":"RelativeHumidityAxis <: HumidityAxis — relative-humidity niche axes (level and range).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.RelativeHumidityAxis"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.RelativeHumidityRange","page":"API","text":"RelativeHumidityRange <: RelativeHumidityAxis — annual range of the monthly relative humidity (BioClimPlus hurs_range; dimensionless).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.RelativeHumidityRange"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.Resource","page":"API","text":"Resource <: Role\n\nMarker for a layer used as a consumable resource.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.Resource"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.Role","page":"API","text":"Role\n\nAbstract supertype of the layer-role markers Condition and Resource.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.Role"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.SavedLandscape-Tuple{GridLandscape, Vector{Random.Xoshiro}}","page":"API","text":"SavedLandscape(gl::GridLandscape, rngs::Vector{Random.Xoshiro})\n\nConvert a GridLandscape to a SavedLandscape for serialisation, preserving the abundance matrix and a snapshot of the per-species RNG streams rngs so a cached run can be resumed with a reproducible random stream.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.SavedLandscape"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.SimpleDemand","page":"API","text":"SimpleDemand <: Abstract1Demand{typeof(1.0/day)}\n\nA simple resource demand — a per-species free-resource rate for each species, /day. Accepts a plain Vector{<:Real} (auto-tagged /day) so the \"no units hassle\" case stays easy.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.SimpleDemand"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.SimpleScenario","page":"API","text":"SimpleScenario <: AbstractScenario\n\nScenario type that applies a uniform rate of change across the entire ecosystem at each timestep. fun is the change function called as fun(eco, timestep, rate), and rate is the magnitude of change per unit time.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.SimpleScenario"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.SimpleSupply","page":"API","text":"SimpleSupply — a free-resource supply rate (`/day`), one float per cell.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.SimpleSupply"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.SiteWaterBalance","page":"API","text":"SiteWaterBalance <: WaterAxis — cumulative site water balance over the year, capped by soil water-holding capacity (BioClimPlus swb; kg·m⁻²).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.SiteWaterBalance"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.SizeDemand","page":"API","text":"SizeDemand <: Abstract1Demand{typeof(1.0/day)}\n\nA resource demand scaled by species size — a per-species free-resource rate for each species, /day (see SimpleDemand; pop_mass_rel/area are used only once, at initial-abundance construction time in SpeciesList, not by the ongoing demand:supply balance).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.SizeDemand"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.SnowWaterEquivalent","page":"API","text":"SnowWaterEquivalent <: WaterAxis — snow water equivalent, the liquid-water amount of the snowpack (BioClimPlus swe; kg·m⁻²).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.SnowWaterEquivalent"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.SolarDemand","page":"API","text":"SolarDemand <: Abstract1Demand{typeof(1.0*kJ/day)}\n\nA vector of per-species solar resource demands, kJ/day.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.SolarDemand"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.SolarRadiation","page":"API","text":"SolarRadiation <: SolarRadiationAxis — surface downwelling shortwave (solar) radiation flux (Climate srad/rsds, BioClimPlus rsds_max/mean/min). Provides a solar supply/demand.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.SolarRadiation"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.SolarRadiationAxis","page":"API","text":"SolarRadiationAxis <: NicheAxis — solar-radiation niche axes (level and range).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.SolarRadiationAxis"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.SolarRadiationRange","page":"API","text":"SolarRadiationRange <: SolarRadiationAxis — annual range of the monthly solar radiation flux (BioClimPlus rsds_range).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.SolarRadiationRange"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.SolarSupply","page":"API","text":"SolarSupply — a static solar-energy supply rate (`kJ/day`).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.SolarSupply"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.SolarTimeSupply","page":"API","text":"SolarTimeSupply — a monthly time-varying solar-energy supply rate (`kJ/day`).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.SolarTimeSupply"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.SpeciesList","page":"API","text":"SpeciesList{TL <: AbstractTolerance, DM <: AbstractDemand,\n            MO <: AbstractMovement, T <: AbstractTypes,\n            P <: AbstractParams} <: AbstractTypes\n\nSpecies list housing all species-specific information. names holds species names, tolerance encodes niche preferences, abun holds current abundances, demand encodes resource needs, types holds the similarity structure, movement describes dispersal, params holds demographic parameters, native flags whether each species is native, and susceptible holds optional disease susceptibility values.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.SpeciesList"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.SpeciesList-Union{Tuple{P}, Tuple{MO}, Tuple{DM}, Tuple{Int64, Int64, Vector{Int64}, DM, MO, P, Vector{Bool}, Vector{Float64}}} where {DM<:EcoSISTEM.AbstractDemand, MO<:EcoSISTEM.AbstractMovement, P<:EcoSISTEM.AbstractParams}","page":"API","text":"SpeciesList(numspecies::Int64, numtraits::Int64, abun::Vector{Int64},\n  demand::DM, movement::MO, params::P, native::Vector{Bool},\n  switch::Vector{Float64})\n\nCreate a SpeciesList for numspecies species with numtraits discrete niche tolerance evolved along a random ultrametric phylogeny. switch controls the rate of trait change along branches. A PhyloBranches similarity structure is computed from the tree. Abundances are provided via abun and resource demands via demand.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.SpeciesList"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.SpeciesList-Union{Tuple{P}, Tuple{MO}, Tuple{DM}, Tuple{Int64, Int64, Vector{Int64}, DM, MO, P, Vector{Bool}}} where {DM<:EcoSISTEM.AbstractDemand, MO<:EcoSISTEM.AbstractMovement, P<:EcoSISTEM.AbstractParams}","page":"API","text":"```julia\nSpeciesList{TL <: AbstractTolerance, DM <: AbstractDemand,\n            MO <: AbstractMovement, T <: AbstractTypes,\n            P <: AbstractParams} <: AbstractTypes\n```\n\nSpecies list housing all species-specific information. `names` holds species names, `tolerance` encodes niche preferences, `abun` holds current abundances, `demand` encodes resource needs, `types` holds the similarity structure, `movement` describes dispersal, `params` holds demographic parameters, `native` flags whether each species is native, and `susceptible` holds optional disease susceptibility values.\n\n\n```julia\nSpeciesList(numspecies::Int64, numtraits::Int64, abun::Vector{Int64},\n  demand::DM, movement::MO, params::P, native::Vector{Bool},\n  switch::Vector{Float64})\n```\n\nCreate a `SpeciesList` for `numspecies` species with `numtraits` discrete niche tolerance evolved along a random ultrametric phylogeny. `switch` controls the rate of trait change along branches. A `PhyloBranches` similarity structure is computed from the tree. Abundances are provided via `abun` and resource demands via `demand`.\n\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.SpeciesList"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.SpeciesList-Union{Tuple{P}, Tuple{MO}, Tuple{DM}, Tuple{TL}, Tuple{Int64, TL, Vector{Int64}, DM, MO, P, Vector{Bool}}} where {TL<:EcoSISTEM.AbstractTolerance, DM<:EcoSISTEM.AbstractDemand, MO<:EcoSISTEM.AbstractMovement, P<:EcoSISTEM.AbstractParams}","page":"API","text":"SpeciesList(numspecies::Int64, tolerance::TL, abun::Vector{Int64}, demand::DM,\n  movement::MO, params::P, native::Vector{Bool})\n\nCreate a SpeciesList from an explicitly supplied trait object tolerance of type AbstractTolerance. Uses UniqueTypes as the similarity structure, treating all species as maximally distinct.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.SpeciesList"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.SpeciesList-Union{Tuple{P}, Tuple{MO}, Tuple{Int64, Int64, Float64, Float64, Float64, Union{Unitful.Quantity{T, 𝐋^2, U}, Unitful.Level{L, S, Unitful.Quantity{T, 𝐋^2, U}} where {L, S}} where {T, U}, MO, P, Vector{Bool}, Vector{Float64}}} where {MO<:EcoSISTEM.AbstractMovement, P<:EcoSISTEM.AbstractParams}","page":"API","text":"SpeciesList(numspecies::Int64, numtraits::Int64, pop_mass::Float64,\n  mean::Float64, var::Float64, area::Unitful.Area, movement::MO,\n  params::P, native::Vector{Bool}, switch::Vector{Float64})\n\nCreate a SpeciesList where body size is evolved as a continuous trait along the phylogeny via Brownian motion with mean mean and variance var. Abundances and resource demands are derived from body size and population mass pop_mass scaled to area. Trait switching rates along the tree are controlled by switch.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.SpeciesList"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.SpeciesList-Union{Tuple{P}, Tuple{T}, Tuple{MO}, Tuple{DM}, Tuple{Int64, Int64, Vector{Int64}, DM, MO, T, P, Vector{Bool}}} where {DM<:EcoSISTEM.AbstractDemand, MO<:EcoSISTEM.AbstractMovement, T<:Diversity.API.AbstractTypes, P<:EcoSISTEM.AbstractParams}","page":"API","text":"SpeciesList(numspecies::Int64, numtraits::Int64, abun::Vector{Int64},\n  demand::DM, movement::MO, phy::T, params::P, native::Vector{Bool})\n\nCreate a SpeciesList with an explicitly supplied similarity structure phy of type AbstractTypes, rather than computing a PhyloBranches similarity internally. Discrete tolerance are still evolved along a random ultrametric tree.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.SpeciesList"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.SupplyCollection2","page":"API","text":"SupplyCollection2{B1, B2} — two supplies over one grid (e.g. solar + water).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.SupplyCollection2"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.TempTolerance","page":"API","text":"TempTolerance — a binned temperature preference (a [`NicheTolerance`](@ref) on `Temperature`, K frame, with a `Trapezoid` response).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.TempTolerance"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.Temperature","page":"API","text":"Temperature <: TemperatureAxis — an absolute temperature (annual/monthly/quarter mean, min, max, or growing-season mean; BioClim 1/5/6/8-11, Climate tavg/tmin/tmax/tas/tasmin/tasmax, BioClimPlus gst; K).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.Temperature"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.TemperatureAxis","page":"API","text":"TemperatureAxis <: NicheAxis — temperature-related niche axes (K unless a leaf overrides).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.TemperatureAxis"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.TemperatureRange","page":"API","text":"TemperatureRange <: TemperatureAxis — a temperature range (max − min): mean diurnal range or annual range (BioClim 2 and 7; K interval).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.TemperatureRange"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.TemperatureSeasonality","page":"API","text":"TemperatureSeasonality <: TemperatureAxis — temperature seasonality, the standard deviation of the monthly mean temperatures (BioClim 4; K).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.TemperatureSeasonality"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.ToleranceCollection2","page":"API","text":"ToleranceCollection2{T1, T2} <: AbstractTolerance{Tuple{T1, T2}}\n\nTrait collection that holds two trait types, TR1 and TR2.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.ToleranceCollection2"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.ToleranceCollection3","page":"API","text":"ToleranceCollection3{T1, T2, T3} <: AbstractTolerance{Tuple{T1, T2, T3}}\n\nTrait collection that holds three trait types, TR1, TR2 and TR3.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.ToleranceCollection3"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.Torus","page":"API","text":"Torus <: BoundaryCondition\n\nA toroidal boundary where species can cross both boundaries.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.Torus"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.Trapeze","page":"API","text":"Trapeze{NF} <: AbstractNicheFit{NF}\n\nwarning: Deprecated\nTrapeze is deprecated and will be removed; use NicheSuitability instead (it pairs with a Trapezoid NicheTolerance).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.Trapeze"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.Trapezoid","page":"API","text":"Trapezoid{T<:Real} <: ContinuousUnivariateDistribution\n\nTrapezoidal distribution as described at https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trapezoidal_distribution.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.Trapezoid"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.TypologyAxis","page":"API","text":"TypologyAxis <: NicheAxis — categorical classification niche axes (discrete class labels; dimensionless, used with a `DiscreteRegime`).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.TypologyAxis"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.Unclassified","page":"API","text":"Unclassified <: NicheAxis\n\nThe default niche axis for a layer built without a declared one (an unclassified layer — it still has data and a unit, but is not modelled on a named axis).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.Unclassified"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.Unif","page":"API","text":"Unif{NF} <: AbstractNicheFit{NF}\n\nwarning: Deprecated\nUnif is deprecated and will be removed; use NicheSuitability instead (it pairs with a Uniform NicheTolerance).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.Unif"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.VaporPressure","page":"API","text":"VaporPressure <: HumidityAxis — near-surface water-vapour partial pressure (Climate vapr; kPa).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.VaporPressure"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.VaporPressureDeficit","page":"API","text":"VaporPressureDeficit <: VaporPressureDeficitAxis — near-surface vapour pressure deficit (Climate vpd, BioClimPlus vpd_max/mean/min; Pa).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.VaporPressureDeficit"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.VaporPressureDeficitAxis","page":"API","text":"VaporPressureDeficitAxis <: HumidityAxis — vapour-pressure-deficit niche axes (level and range).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.VaporPressureDeficitAxis"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.VaporPressureDeficitRange","page":"API","text":"VaporPressureDeficitRange <: VaporPressureDeficitAxis — annual range of the monthly vapour pressure deficit (BioClimPlus vpd_range; Pa).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.VaporPressureDeficitRange"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.WaterAxis","page":"API","text":"WaterAxis <: NicheAxis — umbrella for all water-measuring niche axes (precipitation, humidity, evapotranspiration, moisture, water stocks). A pure grouping node with no unit or resource of its own.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.WaterAxis"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.WaterDemand","page":"API","text":"WaterDemand <: Abstract1Demand{typeof(1.0*L/day)}\n\nA vector of per-species water demands, L/day.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.WaterDemand"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.WaterSupply","page":"API","text":"WaterSupply — a static available-water supply rate (`L/day`).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.WaterSupply"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.WaterTimeSupply","page":"API","text":"WaterTimeSupply — a monthly time-varying available-water supply rate (`L/day`).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.WaterTimeSupply"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.WindSpeed","page":"API","text":"WindSpeed <: WindSpeedAxis — near-surface (10 m) wind speed (Climate wind/sfcWind, BioClimPlus sfcWind_max/mean/min; m·s⁻¹).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.WindSpeed"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.WindSpeedAxis","page":"API","text":"WindSpeedAxis <: NicheAxis — wind-speed niche axes (level and range).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.WindSpeedAxis"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.WindSpeedRange","page":"API","text":"WindSpeedRange <: WindSpeedAxis — annual range of the monthly near-surface wind speed (BioClimPlus sfcWind_range; m·s⁻¹).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.WindSpeedRange"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.additiveFit2","page":"API","text":"additiveFit2{NF1, NF2} <: AbstractNicheFit{Tuple{NF1, NF2}}\n\nType that houses multiple AbstractNicheFits for two trait and regime levels.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.additiveFit2"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.additiveFit3","page":"API","text":"multiplicativeFit3{NF1, NF2, NF3} <: AbstractNicheFit{Tuple{NF1, NF2, NF3}}\n\nType that houses multiple AbstractNicheFits for three trait and regime levels.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.additiveFit3"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.multiplicativeFit2","page":"API","text":"multiplicativeFit2{NF1, NF2} <: AbstractNicheFit{Tuple{NF1, NF2}}\n\nType that houses multiple AbstractNicheFits for two trait and regime levels.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.multiplicativeFit2"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.multiplicativeFit3","page":"API","text":"multiplicativeFit3{NF1, NF2, NF3} <: AbstractNicheFit{Tuple{NF1, NF2, NF3}}\n\nType that houses multiple AbstractNicheFits for three trait and regime levels.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.multiplicativeFit3"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#Base.append!-Tuple{DiversitySet, DataFrames.DataFrame}","page":"API","text":"append!(diversityset::DiversitySet, dat::DataFrame)\n\nAppend a DataFrame of diversity results dat to the data stored in a DiversitySet.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Base.append!"},{"category":"function","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.BM","page":"API","text":"BM(T::Real, σ²::Float64, start::Float64, lab::String=\"\")\n\nEvolve a Real value through Brownian motion, with a starting value,  start, and rate, σ².\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.BM"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.ContinuousEvolve-Tuple{Union{Float64, Unitful.Quantity{Float64}}, Union{Float64, Unitful.Quantity{Float64}}, Phylo.BinaryTree}","page":"API","text":"ContinuousEvolve(val::Union{Float64, Unitful.Quantity{Float64}}, var::Union{Float64, Unitful.Quantity{Float64}}, tree::BinaryTree)\n\nEvolve a continuous trait along a BinaryTree, tree via Brownian motion. Takes in a starting value, val and a variance, var.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.ContinuousEvolve"},{"category":"function","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.DiscreteEvolve","page":"API","text":"DiscreteEvolve(numTraits::Int64, tree::BinaryTree)\n\nEvolve a discrete switching trait along a BinaryTree, tree. Takes in a number of traits, numTraits to be switched between and rate to switch between traits, switch_rate with default value of 0.5.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.DiscreteEvolve"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.GaussTrait-Union{Tuple{A}, Tuple{Type{A}, AbstractVector, AbstractVector}} where A<:NicheAxis","page":"API","text":"GaussTrait(mean, sd)\nGaussTrait(::Type{A}, mean, sd)\n\nwarning: Deprecated\nGaussTrait is deprecated and will be removed. A Gaussian preference is just the Normal case of a NicheTolerance, so use one directly — NicheTolerance(A, Normal, mean, sd) (one unitful vector per parameter, support imputed). This shim forwards to that. GaussTrait(::Type{A}, mean, sd) names the niche axis A explicitly; the axis-less GaussTrait(mean, sd) form takes dimensionless (bare) data as Unclassified, and — for back-compatibility only — infers the axis from a unitful vector's unit (temperature → Temperature, length → Precipitation) with an extra warning, because a NicheTolerance's unit must come from its axis, not its data.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.GaussTrait"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.HabitatLoss-Tuple{EcoSISTEM.AbstractEcosystem, AbstractLayer{EcoSISTEM.Condition}, Union{Unitful.Quantity{T, 𝐓, U}, Unitful.Level{L, S, Unitful.Quantity{T, 𝐓, U}} where {L, S}} where {T, U}}","page":"API","text":"HabitatLoss(eco::AbstractEcosystem, regime::AbstractRegime, timestep::Unitful.Time)\n\nDestroy regime for one timestep of the ecosystem using LayerUpdate information. The regime's dynamics.rate is a loss rate (per unit time); over timestep it gives the per-cell probability that an active cell is lost. That many active cells are drawn at random and have their supply and abundances zeroed.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.HabitatLoss"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.NoChange-Tuple{EcoSISTEM.AbstractEcosystem, AbstractLayer, Union{Unitful.Quantity{T, 𝐓, U}, Unitful.Level{L, S, Unitful.Quantity{T, 𝐓, U}} where {L, S}} where {T, U}}","page":"API","text":"NoChange(eco::AbstractEcosystem, layer::AbstractLayer, timestep::Unitful.Time)\n\nKeep a layer (regime or supply) the same for one timestep of the model.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.NoChange"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.RainfallChange-Tuple{EcoSISTEM.AbstractEcosystem, ContinuousRegime, Union{Unitful.Quantity{T, 𝐓, U}, Unitful.Level{L, S, Unitful.Quantity{T, 𝐓, U}} where {L, S}} where {T, U}}","page":"API","text":"RainfallChange(eco::AbstractEcosystem, regime::ContinuousRegime, timestep::Unitful.Time)\n\nChange the rainfall for one timestep of the ecosystem using LayerUpdate information.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.RainfallChange"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.TempChange-Tuple{EcoSISTEM.AbstractEcosystem, ContinuousRegime, Union{Unitful.Quantity{T, 𝐓, U}, Unitful.Level{L, S, Unitful.Quantity{T, 𝐓, U}} where {L, S}} where {T, U}}","page":"API","text":"TempChange(eco::AbstractEcosystem, regime::ContinuousRegime, timestep::Unitful.Time)\n\nIncrease the temperature for one timestep of the ecosystem using LayerUpdate information.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.TempChange"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.TempFluct-Tuple{EcoSISTEM.AbstractEcosystem, ContinuousRegime, Union{Unitful.Quantity{T, 𝐓, U}, Unitful.Level{L, S, Unitful.Quantity{T, 𝐓, U}} where {L, S}} where {T, U}}","page":"API","text":"TempFluct(eco::AbstractEcosystem, regime::ContinuousRegime, timestep::Unitful.Time)\n\nFluctuate the temperature for one timestep of the ecosystem using LayerUpdate information.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.TempFluct"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM._basedimension-Tuple{Type{<:Union{Unitful.Quantity{T, 𝐋^2 𝐌 𝐓^-3, U}, Unitful.Level{L, S, Unitful.Quantity{T, 𝐋^2 𝐌 𝐓^-3, U}} where {L, S}} where {T, U}}}","page":"API","text":"_basedimension(::Type)\n\nThe physical \"substance\" dimension of a stored Resource element type, with its rate component removed — e.g. dimension(kJ) for typeof(1.0*kJ/day), dimension(L) for typeof(1.0*L/day), NoDims for the free/simple case's bare typeof(1.0/day) (Unitful.Frequency, the built-in T⁻¹ alias — the stored type already carries the rate, not a bare Real, unlike supplytype/demandtype's constructor-input dispatch above). Used only by the rate-dimension guard test (test/test_Energy.jl): every concrete Demand/Supply element type must satisfy dimension(T) / _basedimension(T) == 𝐓^-1 exactly — a genuine rate, not merely \"any negative time exponent\" (energy already embeds 𝐓^-2 in its own definition, so a bare exponent check would be wrong; verified directly: dimension(kJ/d) / dimension(kJ) == 𝐓^-1).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM._basedimension"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM._cellsize-Tuple{Any, Any}","page":"API","text":"_cellsize(lats, longs)\n\nArea-preserving physical side of a grid cell whose cell-centre latitudes and longitudes are lats and longs. The behaviour depends on the units of the coordinates (multiple dispatch):\n\nGeographic (angle) coordinates (degrees): the north–south side is Δlat × 111.32 km; the east–west side uses the true length of a degree of longitude at the grid's centre latitude, Δlong × 111.32 km × cos φ. Returns the geometric mean of the two so that each cell's area is geodetically correct, and reports (@info) how much the east–west length varies from the top to the bottom of the grid.\nProjected (length) coordinates (m, km, …): the grid is already metric, so there is no spherical adjustment — the cell side is simply sqrt(Δlat × Δlong).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM._cellsize"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.abundances-Tuple{CachedEcosystem, Union{Unitful.Quantity{T, 𝐓, U}, Unitful.Level{L, S, Unitful.Quantity{T, 𝐓, U}} where {L, S}} where {T, U}}","page":"API","text":"abundances(cache::CachedEcosystem, tm::Unitful.Time)\n\nExtract abundances for an ecosystem, cache, at a certain point in time, tm. If the abundances for that time are missing from the ecosystem, then the function checks on disk for the last saved version and simulates forward.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.abundances"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.addspecies!-Tuple{Ecosystem, Int64}","page":"API","text":"addspecies!(eco::Ecosystem, abun::Int64)\n\nAdd a new species to an existing Ecosystem with initial abundance abun, copying trait, movement, parameter, demand, and type information from the last existing species.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.addspecies!"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.arenoderecordsempty-Tuple{Phylo.AbstractTree, Vector{String}}","page":"API","text":"arenoderecordsempty(tree::AbstractTree, nodes::Vector{String})\n\nCheck whether the node data records are empty for each node in nodes. Returns a vector of Bool values, one per node.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.arenoderecordsempty"},{"category":"function","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.assetdir","page":"API","text":"EcoSISTEM.assetdir(mod::Module = EcoSISTEM)\n\nPath to the mod subdirectory of EcoSISTEM's single Scratch.jl space, for storing mod-related files (e.g. downloaded data) outside the repository. Using one EcoSISTEM-owned space with per-package subdirectories (rather than a separate space per package) keeps the whole cache under EcoSISTEM's lifecycle — created on first use, reclaimed by Pkg.gc() when EcoSISTEM is removed. mod defaults to EcoSISTEM's own subdirectory.\n\nOn load, EcoSISTEM sets RASTERDATASOURCES_PATH to assetdir(RasterDataSources) (in __init__).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.assetdir"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.assign_traits!-Tuple{Phylo.AbstractTree, DataFrames.DataFrame}","page":"API","text":"assign_traits!(tree::AbstractTree, start::Vector{Float64},\n  σ²::Vector{Float64})\n\nEvolve continuous functional traits through a phylogenetic tree through Brownian motion, with a starting value, start, and rate, σ².\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.assign_traits!"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.assign_traits!-Tuple{Phylo.AbstractTree, Vector{Float64}, DataFrames.DataFrame}","page":"API","text":"assign_traits!(tree::AbstractTree, switch_rate::Vector{Float64},\ntraits::Vector{Vector{String}})\n\nEvolve categorical functional traits through a phylogenetic tree with a specific switching rate.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.assign_traits!"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.bioclimhabitat-Tuple{EcoSISTEM.ClimatePref.ClimateRaster{RasterDataSources.WorldClim{RasterDataSources.BioClim}}, Unitful.Quantity{Float64}, Union{Unitful.Quantity{Float64, 𝐋^2, U}, Unitful.Level{L, S, Unitful.Quantity{Float64, 𝐋^2, U}} where {L, S}} where U, Matrix{Bool}}","page":"API","text":"bioclimhabitat(bioclim::ClimateRaster{WorldClim{BioClim}}, maxsupply::Unitful.Quantity{Float64},\n  area::Unitful.Area{Float64}, active::Matrix{Bool})\n\nAs bioclimhabitat with an explicit active matrix of grid squares, rather than inferring active cells from NaN values in the bioclim data.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.bioclimhabitat"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.bioclimhabitat-Tuple{EcoSISTEM.ClimatePref.ClimateRaster{RasterDataSources.WorldClim{RasterDataSources.BioClim}}, Unitful.Quantity{Float64}, Union{Unitful.Quantity{Float64, 𝐋^2, U}, Unitful.Level{L, S, Unitful.Quantity{Float64, 𝐋^2, U}} where {L, S}} where U}","page":"API","text":"bioclimhabitat(bioclim::ClimateRaster{WorldClim{BioClim}}, maxsupply::Unitful.Quantity{Float64}, area::Unitful.Area{Float64})\n\nCreate a ContinuousRegime, SimpleSupply type abiotic environment from a Worldclim type climate. It either creates a SimpleSupply type filled with the maximum supply value maxsupply or uses a provided supply of type SolarSupply. If a Bool matrix of active grid squares is included, active, this is used, else one is created with all grid cells active.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.bioclimhabitat"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.bioclimhabitat-Union{Tuple{B}, Tuple{EcoSISTEM.ClimatePref.ClimateRaster{RasterDataSources.WorldClim{RasterDataSources.BioClim}}, B, Matrix{Bool}}} where B<:AbstractLayer{EcoSISTEM.Resource}","page":"API","text":"bioclimhabitat(bioclim::ClimateRaster{WorldClim{BioClim}}, supply::B, active::Matrix{Bool}) where B <: AbstractSupply\n\nAs bioclimhabitat but accepts a pre-constructed AbstractSupply object supply rather than computing a supply from a maximum value.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.bioclimhabitat"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.calc_lookup_moves!-Tuple{NoBoundary, Int64, Int64, Int64, EcoSISTEM.AbstractEcosystem, Int64}","page":"API","text":"calc_lookup_moves!(bound, x::Int64, y::Int64, sp::Int64, eco::Ecosystem, abun::Int64)\n\nCalculate the number of moves taken by a species, sp, from a specific grid square location (x, y). There is a boundary condition, bound, which determines how the species can move across space (see AbstractBoundary). The total abundance of individuals is given in abun, which may be the number of births in the timestep, or total individuals.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.calc_lookup_moves!"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.canonicalunit-Tuple{NicheAxis}","page":"API","text":"canonicalunit(::NicheAxis)\ncanonicalunit(::Type{<:Role}, ::NicheAxis)\n\nThe unit a layer on this axis is normalised to when materialised (e.g. temperature → K), or nothing to leave values as-is. The 2-argument form is role-aware: a Condition (a niche tolerance — a descriptive climatological normal) and a Resource (a literal consumable pool, replenished over time) can legitimately want a different canonical unit for the same axis — e.g. Precipitation stays a bare depth (mm) as a Condition, but is a genuine volumetric flow (L/day) as a Resource. It defaults to the 1-argument form for any role/axis combination without a specific override, so existing (implicitly Condition-role) call sites are unaffected.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.canonicalunit"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.checkfile-Tuple{String, Int64}","page":"API","text":"checkfile(file::String, idx::Int)\n\nCheck whether a JLD2 checkpoint file exists in the folder file for checkpoint index idx. Returns true if <idx>.jld2 is present.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.checkfile"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.checkfile-Tuple{String, Missing}","page":"API","text":"checkfile(::String, ::Missing)\n\nCheck whether a cache file exists for a given timepoint. Always returns false when the timepoint is missing.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.checkfile"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.clearcache-Tuple{CachedEcosystem}","page":"API","text":"clearcache(cache::CachedEcosystem)\n\nDelete all JLD2 cache files from the output folder of a CachedEcosystem. Returns a string reporting how many files were removed.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.clearcache"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.combinefit-Tuple{Union{multiplicativeFit2, multiplicativeFit3}}","page":"API","text":"combinefit\n\nFunction that combines the output of multiple niche fits, which varies depending on whether multiplicative, additive etc.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.combinefit"},{"category":"function","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.convert_coords","page":"API","text":"convert_coords(eco, i::Int64, width::Int64)\nconvert_coords(eco, x::Int64, y::Int64, width::Int64)\n\nConvert coordinates from two-dimensional (x,y) format to one dimension (i), or vice versa, using the width of the grid. This function can also be applied to arrays of coordinates.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.convert_coords"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.cyclicChange-Union{Tuple{Arr}, Tuple{V}, Tuple{A}, Tuple{R}, Tuple{EcoSISTEM.AbstractEcosystem, ContinuousLayer{R, A, V, Arr}, Union{Unitful.Quantity{T, 𝐓, U}, Unitful.Level{L, S, Unitful.Quantity{T, 𝐓, U}} where {L, S}} where {T, U}}} where {R, A, V, Arr<:AbstractArray{V, 3}}","page":"API","text":"cyclicChange(eco::AbstractEcosystem, layer::ContinuousLayer, timestep::Unitful.Time)\n\nAdvance a time-varying (monthly) layer — a climate regime or a time supply — by one timestep, wrapping back to the first month once the stored 3-D time series is exhausted (with a warning). The per-source eraChange/worldclimChange names are aliases of this — the time-step-and-wrap logic is identical regardless of source or role.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.cyclicChange"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.demandtype-Tuple{NicheAxis}","page":"API","text":"demandtype(::NicheAxis)\n\nThe AbstractDemand concrete type a species uses to consume this axis' resource, or nothing if the axis is not a resource.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.demandtype"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.dynamics-Tuple{NicheAxis}","page":"API","text":"dynamics(::NicheAxis)\n\nThe default per-timestep change function for a layer on this axis (default NoChange); overridden per layer at build time.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.dynamics"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.emptygridlandscape-Tuple{GridHabitat, SpeciesList}","page":"API","text":"emptygridlandscape(gae::GridHabitat, spplist::SpeciesList)\n\nCreate an empty GridLandscape given a GridHabitat and a SpeciesList.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.emptygridlandscape"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.emptypopulate!-Union{Tuple{R}, Tuple{AB}, Tuple{GridLandscape, SpeciesList, AB, R, Vector{Random.Xoshiro}}} where {AB<:EcoSISTEM.AbstractHabitat, R<:EcoSISTEM.AbstractNicheFit}","page":"API","text":"emptypopulate!(ml::GridLandscape, spplist::SpeciesList, habitat::AB, nichefit::R,\n               rngs::Vector{Random.Xoshiro}) where {AB <: EcoSISTEM.AbstractHabitat, R <: EcoSISTEM.AbstractNicheFit}\n\nPlaceholder population function that leaves the landscape empty and warns.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.emptypopulate!"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.equalpop-Tuple{EqualPop, Any}","page":"API","text":"equalpop(params::EqualPop, numspp)\n\nFunction that takes demographic parameters from type EqualPop and converts them into type PopGrowth based on the number of species (numspp).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.equalpop"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.erahabitat-Tuple{EcoSISTEM.ClimatePref.ERA, Unitful.Quantity{Float64}, Union{Unitful.Quantity{Float64, 𝐋^2, U}, Unitful.Level{L, S, Unitful.Quantity{Float64, 𝐋^2, U}} where {L, S}} where U, Matrix{Bool}}","page":"API","text":"erahabitat(era::ERA, maxsupply::Unitful.Quantity{Float64}, area::Unitful.Area{Float64},\n  active::Matrix{Bool})\n\nAs erahabitat with an explicit active matrix of grid squares, rather than inferring active cells from NaN values in the ERA data.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.erahabitat"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.erahabitat-Tuple{EcoSISTEM.ClimatePref.ERA, Unitful.Quantity{Float64}, Union{Unitful.Quantity{Float64, 𝐋^2, U}, Unitful.Level{L, S, Unitful.Quantity{Float64, 𝐋^2, U}} where {L, S}} where U}","page":"API","text":"erahabitat(era::ERA, maxsupply::Unitful.Quantity{Float64}, area::Unitful.Area{Float64})\n\nCreate a ContinuousRegime, SimpleSupply type abiotic environment from an ERA type climate. It either creates a SimpleSupply type filled with the maximum supply value maxsupply or uses a provided supply of type SolarTimeSupply. If a Bool matrix of active grid squares is included, active, this is used, else one is created with all grid cells active.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.erahabitat"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.erahabitat-Union{Tuple{B}, Tuple{EcoSISTEM.ClimatePref.ERA, B, Matrix{Bool}}} where B<:(ContinuousLayer{EcoSISTEM.Resource, A, V, Arr} where {A, V, Arr<:AbstractArray{V, 3}})","page":"API","text":"erahabitat(era::ERA, supply::B, active::Matrix{Bool}) where B <: AbstractTimeSupply\n\nAs erahabitat but accepts a pre-constructed AbstractTimeSupply object supply rather than computing a supply from a maximum value.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.erahabitat"},{"category":"function","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.gather_abundance","page":"API","text":"gather_abundance(eco::MPIEcosystem)\n\nGather the full abundances matrix onto the root node.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.gather_abundance"},{"category":"function","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.gather_diversity","page":"API","text":"gather_diversity(eco::MPIEcosystem, divmeasure::F, q) where F <: Function\n\nGather diversity calculated by divmeasure at value q from all MPI nodes onto the root node (rank 0), combining subcommunity diversity values using a power mean weighted by total abundances across nodes.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.gather_diversity"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.generate_storage-Tuple{Ecosystem, Int64, Int64, Int64}","page":"API","text":"generate_storage(eco::Ecosystem, qs::Int64, times::Int64, reps::Int64)\n\nAllocate a float array of shape (gridSize, qs, times, reps) for recording diversity values across the ecosystem eco for qs diversity orders over multiple timesteps and replicate runs.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.generate_storage"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.generate_storage-Tuple{Ecosystem, Int64, Int64}","page":"API","text":"generate_storage(eco::Ecosystem, times::Int64, reps::Int64)\n\nAllocate an integer array of shape (numSpecies, gridSize, times, reps) for recording species abundances across the ecosystem eco over multiple timesteps and replicate runs.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.generate_storage"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.genlookups-Tuple{AbstractLayer{EcoSISTEM.Condition}, GaussianKernel}","page":"API","text":"genlookups(regime::AbstractRegime, kernel::GaussianMovement)\n\nGenerate lookup tables, which hold information on the probability of moving to neighbouring squares.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.genlookups"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.geom_mean_abun-Tuple{Ecosystem, Vector{Float64}}","page":"API","text":"geom_mean_abun(eco::Ecosystem, qs::Vector{Float64})\n\nCalculate the geometric mean abundance for the entire ecosystem.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.geom_mean_abun"},{"category":"function","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.get_neighbours","page":"API","text":"get_neighbours(mat::Matrix, x_coord::Vector{Int64}, y_coord::Vector{Int64},\n    chess::Int64=4)\n\nAs get_neighbours but accepts vectors of coordinates and returns the combined neighbours for all positions.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.get_neighbours"},{"category":"function","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.get_neighbours-2","page":"API","text":"get_neighbours(mat::Matrix, x_coord::Int64, y_coord::Int64, chess::Int64=4)\n\nGet the neighbours of a grid square in a matrix in 4 or 8 directions\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.get_neighbours"},{"category":"function","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.get_traits","page":"API","text":"get_traits(tree::AbstractTree, tips::Bool=true)\n\nRetrieve functional traits assigned to a phylogenetic tree, either just tips or all nodes.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.get_traits"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.getavailablesupply-Tuple{GridHabitat}","page":"API","text":"getavailablesupply(gae::GridHabitat)\n\nReturn the available resource supply from a GridHabitat.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.getavailablesupply"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.getboundary-Tuple{BirthOnlyMovement}","page":"API","text":"getboundary(m::AbstractMovement)\n\nExtract the boundary condition from a movement type.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.getboundary"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.getdemand-Tuple{SpeciesList}","page":"API","text":"getdemand(sppl::SpeciesList)\n\nReturn the total resource usage for the species list sppl, combining abundances with per-species resource demands.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.getdemand"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.getdimension-Tuple{EcoSISTEM.AbstractEcosystem}","page":"API","text":"getdimension(eco::Ecosystem)\n\nExtract dimension of regime from Ecosystem object.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.getdimension"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.getdispersaldist-Tuple{EcoSISTEM.AbstractEcosystem, Int64}","page":"API","text":"getdispersaldist(eco::Ecosystem)\n\nExtract average dispersal distance of species from Ecosystem object. Returns a vector of distances, unless a specific species is provided as a String or Integer.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.getdispersaldist"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.getdispersaldist-Tuple{EcoSISTEM.AbstractEcosystem, String}","page":"API","text":"getdispersaldist(eco::Ecosystem)\n\nExtract average dispersal distance of species from Ecosystem object. Returns a vector of distances, unless a specific species is provided as a String or Integer.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.getdispersaldist"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.getdispersalvar-Tuple{EcoSISTEM.AbstractEcosystem, Int64}","page":"API","text":"getdispersalvar(eco::Ecosystem)\n\nExtract dispersal varaince of species from Ecosystem object. Returns a vector of distances, unless a specific species is provided as a String or Integer.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.getdispersalvar"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.getdispersalvar-Tuple{EcoSISTEM.AbstractEcosystem, String}","page":"API","text":"getdispersalvar(eco::Ecosystem)\n\nExtract dispersal varaince of species from Ecosystem object. Returns a vector of distances, unless a specific species is provided as a String or Integer.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.getdispersalvar"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.getdist-Tuple{NicheTolerance, Int64}","page":"API","text":"getdist(tolerance::NicheTolerance, sp::Int64)\n\nReturn the pre-built response distribution for species sp from a NicheTolerance trait. This is what _suitability uses in the hot loop — a plain vector fetch, no per-call construction or allocation.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.getdist"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.getgridsize-Tuple{EcoSISTEM.AbstractEcosystem}","page":"API","text":"getgridsize(eco::Ecosystem)\n\nExtract grid cell size of regime from Ecosystem object.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.getgridsize"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.getkernels-Tuple{BirthOnlyMovement}","page":"API","text":"getkernels(m::AbstractMovement)\n\nExtract the vector of dispersal kernels from a movement type.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.getkernels"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.getlookup-Tuple{EcoSISTEM.AbstractEcosystem, Int64}","page":"API","text":"getlookup(eco::Ecosystem)\n\nExtract movement lookup table of species from Ecosystem object.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.getlookup"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.getlookup-Tuple{EcoSISTEM.AbstractEcosystem, String}","page":"API","text":"getlookup(eco::Ecosystem)\n\nExtract movement lookup table of species from Ecosystem object.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.getlookup"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.getnichefit-Tuple{EcoSISTEM.AbstractEcosystem}","page":"API","text":"getnichefit(eco::Ecosystem)\n\nExtract niche fits.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.getnichefit"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.getpref-Tuple{DiscreteTolerance, Int64}","page":"API","text":"getpref(tolerance::DiscreteTolerance, sp::Int64)\n\nExtract the discrete niche preference value for species sp from a DiscreteTolerance.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.getpref"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.getpref-Tuple{LandCoverTolerance, Int64}","page":"API","text":"getpref(tolerance::LandCoverTolerance, sp::Int64)\n\nExtract the land cover preference values for species sp from an LandCoverTolerance.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.getpref"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.getpref-Tuple{NicheTolerance, Int64}","page":"API","text":"getpref(tolerance::NicheTolerance, sp::Int64)\n\nReturn the parameters of species sp's response distribution from a NicheTolerance trait (a back-compat shim over getdist; the parameters are no longer stored separately).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.getpref"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.getpref-Union{Tuple{T}, Tuple{T, Symbol}} where T<:EcoSISTEM.AbstractTolerance","page":"API","text":"getpref(tolerance::T, field::Symbol) where T <: AbstractTolerance\n\nExtract trait preferences for all species in the ecosystem.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.getpref"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.getregime-Tuple{ContinuousTimeRegime{C} where C, Int64}","page":"API","text":"getregime(regime::ContinuousTimeRegime, pos::Int64)\n\nReturn the regime value at position pos for the current time slice of a ContinuousTimeRegime.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.getregime"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.getregime-Tuple{EcoSISTEM.AbstractEcosystem}","page":"API","text":"getregime(eco::Ecosystem)\n\nExtract regime from Ecosystem object.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.getregime"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.getregime-Union{Tuple{H}, Tuple{H, Int64}} where H<:AbstractLayer{EcoSISTEM.Condition}","page":"API","text":"getregime(regime::H, pos::Int64) where H <: AbstractRegime\n\nReturn the regime value at 1D grid position pos, converting to 2D coordinates internally.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.getregime"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.getregime-Union{Tuple{H}, Tuple{H, Symbol}} where H<:AbstractLayer{EcoSISTEM.Condition}","page":"API","text":"getregime(regime::H, pos::Int64) where H <: AbstractRegime\n\nReturn the regime value at 1D grid position pos, converting to 2D coordinates internally.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.getregime"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.getrelationship-Union{Tuple{R}, Tuple{R, Symbol}} where R<:EcoSISTEM.AbstractNicheFit","page":"API","text":"getrelationship(nichefit::R, field::Symbol) where R <: AbstractNicheFit\n\nExtract the trait nichefit of all species in the ecosystem.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.getrelationship"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.getrng-Tuple{EcoSISTEM.AbstractEcosystem, Int64}","page":"API","text":"getrng(eco::AbstractEcosystem, sp::Int64)\n\nReturn the per-species random number generator for global species index sp. Because each species has its own stream and is processed by exactly one task per timestep, random draws are both thread-safe and reproducible independent of the number of threads or MPI processes (see makerngs).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.getrng"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.getsize-Tuple{EcoSISTEM.AbstractEcosystem}","page":"API","text":"getsize(eco::Ecosystem)\n\nExtract size of regime from Ecosystem object.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.getsize"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.getsupply-Tuple{EcoSISTEM.AbstractEcosystem}","page":"API","text":"getsupply(eco::Ecosystem)\n\nExtract supply from Ecosystem object.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.getsupply"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.gettimes-Tuple{DiversitySet}","page":"API","text":"gettimes(diversityset::DiversitySet)\n\nReturn the timepoints in a DiversitySet for which diversity has not yet been calculated. If a previously saved Feather file of results is found, only times beyond the latest recorded time are returned.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.gettimes"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.landcoverhabitat-Union{Tuple{A}, Tuple{T}, Tuple{EcoSISTEM.ClimatePref.ClimateRaster{T, A}, Unitful.Quantity{Float64}, Union{Unitful.Quantity{T, 𝐋^2, U}, Unitful.Level{L, S, Unitful.Quantity{T, 𝐋^2, U}} where {L, S}} where {T, U}, Matrix{Bool}}} where {T<:(RasterDataSources.EarthEnv{<:RasterDataSources.LandCover}), A}","page":"API","text":"landcoverhabitat(landcover::ClimateRaster{<:EarthEnv{<:LandCover}}, maxsupply::Unitful.Quantity{Float64}, area::Unitful.Area,\n  active::Matrix{Bool})\n\nAs landcoverhabitat with an explicit active matrix of grid squares, rather than setting all cells active.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.landcoverhabitat"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.landcoverhabitat-Union{Tuple{A}, Tuple{T}, Tuple{EcoSISTEM.ClimatePref.ClimateRaster{T, A}, Unitful.Quantity{Float64}, Union{Unitful.Quantity{T, 𝐋^2, U}, Unitful.Level{L, S, Unitful.Quantity{T, 𝐋^2, U}} where {L, S}} where {T, U}}} where {T<:(RasterDataSources.EarthEnv{<:RasterDataSources.LandCover}), A}","page":"API","text":"landcoverhabitat(landcover::ClimateRaster{<:EarthEnv{<:LandCover}}, maxsupply::Unitful.Quantity{Float64}, area::Unitful.Area)\n\nCreate a DiscreteRegime, SimpleSupply type abiotic environment from a land cover ClimateRaster dataset. It creates a DiscreteRegime regime from the land cover array and a SimpleSupply type filled with the maximum supply value maxsupply, scaled to the given area. If a Bool matrix of active grid squares is included, active, this is used, else one is created with all grid cells active.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.landcoverhabitat"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.landcoverhabitat-Union{Tuple{B}, Tuple{A}, Tuple{T}, Tuple{EcoSISTEM.ClimatePref.ClimateRaster{T, A}, B, Matrix{Bool}}} where {T<:(RasterDataSources.EarthEnv{<:RasterDataSources.LandCover}), A, B<:AbstractLayer{EcoSISTEM.Resource}}","page":"API","text":"landcoverhabitat(landcover::ClimateRaster{<:EarthEnv{<:LandCover}}, supply::B, active::Matrix{Bool}) where B <: AbstractSupply\n\nAs landcoverhabitat but accepts a pre-constructed AbstractSupply object supply rather than computing a supply from a maximum value.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.landcoverhabitat"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.loadfile-Tuple{CachedEcosystem, String, Int64, Tuple}","page":"API","text":"loadfile(cache::CachedEcosystem, file::String, idx::Int, dim::Tuple)\n\nLoad a cached GridLandscape from the folder file for checkpoint index idx, reshaping the abundance matrix to dimensions dim. The saved per-species RNG streams are restored into cache.rngs so the resumed run continues a reproducible random stream.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.loadfile"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.makerngs-Tuple{Integer, Integer}","page":"API","text":"makerngs(seed::Integer, n::Integer)\n\nBuild a vector of n independent, deterministically-seeded random number generators, one per species. Species j is seeded as Xoshiro(hash((seed, j))) so its random stream is a pure function of (seed, j) — independent of how species are distributed across threads or MPI processes. This is what makes simulation results reproducible across different thread and process counts (each species is always processed by exactly one task on one rank, drawing in a fixed cell order). See getrng.\n\nNote: this per-species scheme is sufficient only because no single species' draws are ever split across ranks/tasks. If a species' cells were ever partitioned across ranks, a per-(species, cell) counter-based generator would be needed instead.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.makerngs"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.makeunique-Tuple{Ecosystem}","page":"API","text":"makeunique(eco::Ecosystem)\n\nConvert type of similarity in SpeciesList to UniqueTypes, i.e. an identity matrix.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.makeunique"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.mean_abun-Tuple{Ecosystem, Vector{Float64}}","page":"API","text":"mean_abun(eco::Ecosystem, qs::Vector{Float64})\n\nCalculate the mean arithmetic abundance for the entire ecosystem.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.mean_abun"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.meta_shannon-Tuple{Ecosystem, Vector{Float64}}","page":"API","text":"meta_shannon(eco::Ecosystem, qs::Vector{Float64})\n\nCalculate the Shannon entropy for the entire ecosystem.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.meta_shannon"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.meta_simpson-Tuple{Ecosystem, Vector{Float64}}","page":"API","text":"meta_simpson(eco::Ecosystem, qs::Vector{Float64})\n\nCalculate the Simpson diversity for the entire ecosystem.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.meta_simpson"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.meta_speciesrichness-Tuple{Ecosystem, Vector{Float64}}","page":"API","text":"meta_speciesrichness(eco::Ecosystem, qs::Vector{Float64})\n\nCalculate the species richness for the entire ecosystem.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.meta_speciesrichness"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.move!-Tuple{EcoSISTEM.AbstractEcosystem, AlwaysMovement, Int64, Int64, Matrix{Int64}, Int64}","page":"API","text":"move!(eco::Ecosystem, ::AbstractMovement, i::Int64, sp::Int64, grd::Matrix{Int64}, abun::Int64)\n\nCalculate the movement of species sp from a given position in the landscape i, using the lookup table found in the Ecosystem and updating the movement patterns on a cached grid, grd. Optionally, a number of births can be provided, so that movement only takes place as part of the birth process, instead of the entire population\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.move!"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.nfmatch-Tuple{SpeciesList, EcoSISTEM.AbstractNicheFit}","page":"API","text":"nfmatch(sppl::SpeciesList, traitrel::AbstractNicheFit)\n\nCheck that the types of a tolerance list and trait nichefit list are the same for a species list (sppl) and trait nichefit (traitrel).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.nfmatch"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.pair-Tuple{Any}","page":"API","text":"pair(vec)\n\nSplit a vector into consecutive overlapping pairs, returning a matrix with one pair per row. Used to traverse root-to-tip paths branch by branch.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.pair"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.param_units-Tuple{Type{<:Distributions.UnivariateDistribution}, Unitful.Units}","page":"API","text":"param_units(D, support_units; probes = _default_probes(D))\n\nThe absolute unit of each parameter of distribution D given a support of support_units, inferred by parameter role (see param_roles_resolved): a location or scale parameter carries the absolute support unit (K for °C), a rate carries its inverse, and a shape parameter is dimensionless — so a shape-only family (Beta, LogNormal, …) is all-NoUnits. This is the introspection companion to read_distribution, which performs the actual (affine-aware) value conversion when a distribution is read from bare parameters.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.param_units"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.pd-Tuple{Ecosystem, Vector{Float64}}","page":"API","text":"pd(eco::Ecosystem, qs::Vector{Float64})\n\nCalculate Faith's phylogenetic diversity (PD) for the entire ecosystem.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.pd"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.peakedgradhabitat-Tuple{Union{Unitful.Quantity{Float64, 𝚯, U}, Unitful.Level{L, S, Unitful.Quantity{Float64, 𝚯, U}} where {L, S}} where U, Union{Unitful.Quantity{Float64, 𝚯, U}, Unitful.Level{L, S, Unitful.Quantity{Float64, 𝚯, U}} where {L, S}} where U, Tuple{Int64, Int64}, Unitful.Quantity{Float64}, Union{Unitful.Quantity{Float64, 𝐋^2, U}, Unitful.Level{L, S, Unitful.Quantity{Float64, 𝐋^2, U}} where {L, S}} where U, Unitful.Quantity{Float64, 𝚯 𝐓^-1}, Matrix{Bool}}","page":"API","text":"peakedgradhabitat(minT::Unitful.Temperature{Float64},\n   maxT::Unitful.Temperature{Float64},\n   dimension::Tuple{Int64, Int64}, maxsupply::Unitful.Quantity{Float64},\n   area::Unitful.Area{Float64}, rate::Quantity{Float64, 𝚯*𝐓^-1},\n   active::Matrix{Bool})\n\nCreate a peaked temperature gradient ContinuousRegime, SimpleSupply type abiotic environment. Given a minT and maxT temperature, it generates a gradient with minima at the top and bottom, peaking at maxT in the middle. It creates a ContinuousRegime environment with dimensions dimension and a specified area area. It also creates a SimpleSupply type filled with the maximum supply value maxsupply. The rate of temperature change is specified using the parameter rate. If a Bool matrix of active grid squares is included, active, this is used, else one is created with all grid cells active.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.peakedgradhabitat"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.peakedgradhabitat-Tuple{Union{Unitful.Quantity{Float64, 𝚯, U}, Unitful.Level{L, S, Unitful.Quantity{Float64, 𝚯, U}} where {L, S}} where U, Union{Unitful.Quantity{Float64, 𝚯, U}, Unitful.Level{L, S, Unitful.Quantity{Float64, 𝚯, U}} where {L, S}} where U, Tuple{Int64, Int64}, Unitful.Quantity{Float64}, Union{Unitful.Quantity{Float64, 𝐋^2, U}, Unitful.Level{L, S, Unitful.Quantity{Float64, 𝐋^2, U}} where {L, S}} where U, Unitful.Quantity{Float64, 𝚯 𝐓^-1}}","page":"API","text":"peakedgradhabitat(minT::Unitful.Temperature{Float64},\n   maxT::Unitful.Temperature{Float64},\n   dimension::Tuple{Int64, Int64}, maxsupply::Unitful.Quantity{Float64},\n   area::Unitful.Area{Float64}, rate::Quantity{Float64, 𝚯*𝐓^-1},\n   active::Matrix{Bool})\n\nCreate a peaked temperature gradient ContinuousRegime, SimpleSupply type abiotic environment. Given a minT and maxT temperature, it generates a gradient with minima at the top and bottom, peaking at maxT in the middle. It creates a ContinuousRegime environment with dimensions dimension and a specified area area. It also creates a SimpleSupply type filled with the maximum supply value maxsupply. The rate of temperature change is specified using the parameter rate. If a Bool matrix of active grid squares is included, active, this is used, else one is created with all grid cells active.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.peakedgradhabitat"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.populate!-Union{Tuple{R}, Tuple{AB}, Tuple{GridLandscape, SpeciesList, AB, R, Vector{Random.Xoshiro}}} where {AB<:EcoSISTEM.AbstractHabitat, R<:EcoSISTEM.AbstractNicheFit}","page":"API","text":"populate!(ml::GridLandscape, spplist::SpeciesList, habitat::AbstractHabitat,\n          nichefit::AbstractNicheFit, rngs::Vector{Random.Xoshiro})\npopulate!(ml::GridLandscape, spplist::SpeciesList,\n          habitat::GridHabitat{H, SupplyCollection2{B1, B2}}, nichefit, rngs)\n\nPopulate the grid landscape ml by randomly scattering each species' total abundance (taken from spplist.abun) across the grid cells, choosing each cell with probability proportional to its available resource supply. Inactive cells are given zero probability, so no individuals are placed outside the habitable region. Each species is drawn from its own generator in rngs, so the result is reproducible and independent of the number of threads or MPI processes.\n\nnichefit is unused by these resource-based methods; it is accepted only so that they share a signature with tolerancepopulate! and can be passed interchangeably as the population function when constructing an Ecosystem. For a two-supply environment (SupplyCollection2) the sampling weight of a cell is the product of its two separately normalised supplies.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.populate!"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.raingrad-Tuple{Union{Unitful.Quantity{Float64, 𝐋, U}, Unitful.Level{L, S, Unitful.Quantity{Float64, 𝐋, U}} where {L, S}} where U, Union{Unitful.Quantity{Float64, 𝐋, U}, Unitful.Level{L, S, Unitful.Quantity{Float64, 𝐋, U}} where {L, S}} where U, Union{Unitful.Quantity{Float64, 𝐋, U}, Unitful.Level{L, S, Unitful.Quantity{Float64, 𝐋, U}} where {L, S}} where U, Tuple{Int64, Int64}, Unitful.Quantity{Float64, 𝐋 𝐓^-1}}","page":"API","text":"raingrad(minR::Unitful.Length{Float64}, maxR::Unitful.Length{Float64},\n  size::Unitful.Length{Float64},\n  dim::Tuple{Int64, Int64}, rate::Quantity{Float64, 𝐋*𝐓^-1})\n\nCreate a ContinuousRegime regime with a rainfall gradient.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.raingrad"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.raingradhabitat-Tuple{Union{Unitful.Quantity{Float64, 𝐋, U}, Unitful.Level{L, S, Unitful.Quantity{Float64, 𝐋, U}} where {L, S}} where U, Union{Unitful.Quantity{Float64, 𝐋, U}, Unitful.Level{L, S, Unitful.Quantity{Float64, 𝐋, U}} where {L, S}} where U, Tuple{Int64, Int64}, Union{Unitful.Quantity{Float64, 𝐋^2, U}, Unitful.Level{L, S, Unitful.Quantity{Float64, 𝐋^2, U}} where {L, S}} where U, Unitful.Quantity{Float64, 𝐋 𝐓^-1}, Matrix{Bool}}","page":"API","text":"raingradhabitat(minR::Unitful.Length{Float64}, maxR::Unitful.Length{Float64},\n  dimension::Tuple{Int64, Int64}, area::Unitful.Area{Float64},\n  rate::Quantity{Float64, 𝐋*𝐓^-1}, active::Matrix{Bool})\n\nAs raingradhabitat but uses the rainfall values from the gradient directly as a WaterSupply, rather than computing a supply from a separate maxsupply value.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.raingradhabitat"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.raingradhabitat-Tuple{Union{Unitful.Quantity{Float64, 𝐋, U}, Unitful.Level{L, S, Unitful.Quantity{Float64, 𝐋, U}} where {L, S}} where U, Union{Unitful.Quantity{Float64, 𝐋, U}, Unitful.Level{L, S, Unitful.Quantity{Float64, 𝐋, U}} where {L, S}} where U, Tuple{Int64, Int64}, Union{Unitful.Quantity{Float64, 𝐋^2, U}, Unitful.Level{L, S, Unitful.Quantity{Float64, 𝐋^2, U}} where {L, S}} where U, Unitful.Quantity{Float64, 𝐋 𝐓^-1}}","page":"API","text":"```julia\nraingradhabitat(minR::Unitful.Length{Float64},\n  maxR::Unitful.Length{Float64},\n  dimension::Tuple{Int64, Int64}, maxsupply::Unitful.Quantity{Float64},\n  area::Unitful.Area{Float64}, rate::Quantity{Float64, 𝐋*𝐓^-1},\n  active::Matrix{Bool})\n```\n\nCreate a rainfall gradient [`ContinuousRegime`](@ref), [`SimpleSupply`](@ref) type abiotic environment. Given a `minR` and `maxR` rainfall, it generates a gradient from minimum at the bottom to maximum at the top. It creates a [`ContinuousRegime`](@ref) environment with dimensions `dimension` and a specified area `area`. It also creates a [`SimpleSupply`](@ref) type filled with the maximum supply value `maxsupply`. The rate of rainfall change is specified using the parameter `rate`. If a Bool matrix of active grid squares is included, `active`, this is used, else one is created with all grid cells active.\n\n\n```julia\nraingradhabitat(minR::Unitful.Length{Float64}, maxR::Unitful.Length{Float64},\n  dimension::Tuple{Int64, Int64}, area::Unitful.Area{Float64},\n  rate::Quantity{Float64, 𝐋*𝐓^-1}, active::Matrix{Bool})\n```\n\nAs [`raingradhabitat`](@ref) but uses the rainfall values from the gradient directly as a [`WaterSupply`](@ref), rather than computing a supply from a separate `maxsupply` value.\n\n\n```julia\nraingradhabitat(minR::Unitful.Length{Float64},\n  maxR::Unitful.Length{Float64},\n  dimension::Tuple{Int64, Int64}, maxsupply::Unitful.Quantity{Float64},\n  area::Unitful.Area{Float64}, rate::Quantity{Float64, 𝐋*𝐓^-1},\n  active::Matrix{Bool})\n```\n\nCreate a rainfall gradient [`ContinuousRegime`](@ref), [`SimpleSupply`](@ref) type abiotic environment. Given a `minR` and `maxR` rainfall, it generates a gradient from minimum at the bottom to maximum at the top. It creates a [`ContinuousRegime`](@ref) environment with dimensions `dimension` and a specified area `area`. It also creates a [`SimpleSupply`](@ref) type filled with the maximum supply value `maxsupply`. The rate of rainfall change is specified using the parameter `rate`. If a Bool matrix of active grid squares is included, `active`, this is used, else one is created with all grid cells active.\n\n```julia\nraingradhabitat(minR::Unitful.Length{Float64}, maxR::Unitful.Length{Float64},\n  dimension::Tuple{Int64, Int64}, area::Unitful.Area{Float64},\n  rate::Quantity{Float64, 𝐋*𝐓^-1}, active::Matrix{Bool})\n```\n\nAs [`raingradhabitat`](@ref) but uses the rainfall values from the gradient directly as a [`WaterSupply`](@ref), rather than computing a supply from a separate `maxsupply` value.\n\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.raingradhabitat"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.raingradhabitat-Tuple{Union{Unitful.Quantity{Float64, 𝐋, U}, Unitful.Level{L, S, Unitful.Quantity{Float64, 𝐋, U}} where {L, S}} where U, Union{Unitful.Quantity{Float64, 𝐋, U}, Unitful.Level{L, S, Unitful.Quantity{Float64, 𝐋, U}} where {L, S}} where U, Tuple{Int64, Int64}, Unitful.Quantity{Float64}, Union{Unitful.Quantity{Float64, 𝐋^2, U}, Unitful.Level{L, S, Unitful.Quantity{Float64, 𝐋^2, U}} where {L, S}} where U, Unitful.Quantity{Float64, 𝐋 𝐓^-1}, Matrix{Bool}}","page":"API","text":"raingradhabitat(minR::Unitful.Length{Float64},\n  maxR::Unitful.Length{Float64},\n  dimension::Tuple{Int64, Int64}, maxsupply::Unitful.Quantity{Float64},\n  area::Unitful.Area{Float64}, rate::Quantity{Float64, 𝐋*𝐓^-1},\n  active::Matrix{Bool})\n\nCreate a rainfall gradient ContinuousRegime, SimpleSupply type abiotic environment. Given a minR and maxR rainfall, it generates a gradient from minimum at the bottom to maximum at the top. It creates a ContinuousRegime environment with dimensions dimension and a specified area area. It also creates a SimpleSupply type filled with the maximum supply value maxsupply. The rate of rainfall change is specified using the parameter rate. If a Bool matrix of active grid squares is included, active, this is used, else one is created with all grid cells active.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.raingradhabitat"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.raingradhabitat-Tuple{Union{Unitful.Quantity{Float64, 𝐋, U}, Unitful.Level{L, S, Unitful.Quantity{Float64, 𝐋, U}} where {L, S}} where U, Union{Unitful.Quantity{Float64, 𝐋, U}, Unitful.Level{L, S, Unitful.Quantity{Float64, 𝐋, U}} where {L, S}} where U, Tuple{Int64, Int64}, Unitful.Quantity{Float64}, Union{Unitful.Quantity{Float64, 𝐋^2, U}, Unitful.Level{L, S, Unitful.Quantity{Float64, 𝐋^2, U}} where {L, S}} where U, Unitful.Quantity{Float64, 𝐋 𝐓^-1}}","page":"API","text":"```julia\nraingradhabitat(minR::Unitful.Length{Float64},\n  maxR::Unitful.Length{Float64},\n  dimension::Tuple{Int64, Int64}, maxsupply::Unitful.Quantity{Float64},\n  area::Unitful.Area{Float64}, rate::Quantity{Float64, 𝐋*𝐓^-1},\n  active::Matrix{Bool})\n```\n\nCreate a rainfall gradient [`ContinuousRegime`](@ref), [`SimpleSupply`](@ref) type abiotic environment. Given a `minR` and `maxR` rainfall, it generates a gradient from minimum at the bottom to maximum at the top. It creates a [`ContinuousRegime`](@ref) environment with dimensions `dimension` and a specified area `area`. It also creates a [`SimpleSupply`](@ref) type filled with the maximum supply value `maxsupply`. The rate of rainfall change is specified using the parameter `rate`. If a Bool matrix of active grid squares is included, `active`, this is used, else one is created with all grid cells active.\n\n\n```julia\nraingradhabitat(minR::Unitful.Length{Float64}, maxR::Unitful.Length{Float64},\n  dimension::Tuple{Int64, Int64}, area::Unitful.Area{Float64},\n  rate::Quantity{Float64, 𝐋*𝐓^-1}, active::Matrix{Bool})\n```\n\nAs [`raingradhabitat`](@ref) but uses the rainfall values from the gradient directly as a [`WaterSupply`](@ref), rather than computing a supply from a separate `maxsupply` value.\n\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.raingradhabitat"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.randomniches-Tuple{Tuple, Vector{Int64}, Float64, Vector, Union{Unitful.Quantity{T, 𝐋, U}, Unitful.Level{L, S, Unitful.Quantity{T, 𝐋, U}} where {L, S}} where {T, U}}","page":"API","text":"randomniches(dimension::Tuple, types::Vector{Int64}, clumpiness::Float64,\n    weights::Vector, gridsquaresize::Unitful.Length)\n\nCreate a DiscreteRegime regime of dimension dimension, made up of integer niche types types with relative weightings weights and spatial clumpiness controlled by clumpiness. Cell size is set by gridsquaresize.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.randomniches"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.read_distribution-Tuple{Type{<:Distributions.UnivariateDistribution}, Any, Any}","page":"API","text":"read_distribution(D, support_unit, bare; canonical = absoluteunit(support_unit),\n                  offset = nothing, scale = nothing, probes = nothing)\n\nBuild one species' response distribution of type D in the canonical (absolute) frame from bare parameter values interpreted in support_unit. Roles (param_roles_resolved) drive the per-parameter conversion; a shape-only distribution (no location/scale/rate role — e.g. Beta, LogNormal) is placed on the dimensioned axis via LocationScale, requiring offset (reference position) + scale (reference width) to produce dist * scale + offset.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.read_distribution"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.regimeupdate!-Tuple{EcoSISTEM.AbstractEcosystem, Union{Unitful.Quantity{T, 𝐓, U}, Unitful.Level{L, S, Unitful.Quantity{T, 𝐓, U}} where {L, S}} where {T, U}}","page":"API","text":"regimeupdate!(eco::AbstractEcosystem, timestep::Unitful.Time)\n\nUpdate the regime of an ecosystem for one timestep.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.regimeupdate!"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.repopulate!-Tuple{Ecosystem}","page":"API","text":"repopulate!(eco::Ecosystem)\nrepopulate!(eco::Ecosystem, abun::Int64)\n\nRepopulate an ecosystem eco by redistributing abundances according to resource availability. If an abun parameter is given, that number of individuals of the final species is added at randomly sampled locations instead.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.repopulate!"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.reroot!-Tuple{Phylo.AbstractTree, String}","page":"API","text":"reroot!(tree::AbstractTree, node::String)\n\nReroot a phylogenetic tree by removing and recreating node, then attaching a new root node \"NewRoot\" above the original root.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.reroot!"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.resetrate!-Tuple{EcoSISTEM.AbstractEcosystem, Unitful.Quantity{Float64, Unitful.Dimensions{(Unitful.Dimension{:Time}(-1//1),)}}}","page":"API","text":"resetrate!(eco::Ecosystem, rate::Quantity{Float64, typeof(𝐓^-1)})\n\nReset the rate of regime change for a species.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.resetrate!"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.resettraits!-Tuple{Phylo.AbstractTree}","page":"API","text":"resettraits!(tree::AbstractTree)\n\nClear all node data records in the tree, resetting every node to an empty DataFrame.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.resettraits!"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.resource_adjustment-Tuple{EcoSISTEM.AbstractEcosystem, AbstractLayer{EcoSISTEM.Resource}, Int64, Int64}","page":"API","text":"resource_adjustment(eco::Ecosystem, supply::AbstractSupply, i::Int64, sp::Int64)\n\nCalculate how much birth and death rates should be adjusted by, according to how much resource is available, supply, in the grid square, i, and how much resource the species, sp, requires.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.resource_adjustment"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.resupply!-Tuple{Ecosystem, Union{Float64, Unitful.Quantity{Float64}}, Tuple{Int64, Int64}}","page":"API","text":"resupply!(eco::Ecosystem, supply::Union{Float64, Unitful.Quantity{Float64}}, grid::Tuple{Int64, Int64})\n\nRefill an ecosystem eco, with resource from a supply value, supply and a grid size.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.resupply!"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.root_to_tips-Tuple{Any}","page":"API","text":"root_to_tips(tree)\n\nReturn all root-to-tip paths in a phylogenetic tree as a vector of node-name vectors, one per tip.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.root_to_tips"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.runscenario!-Tuple{Ecosystem, Union{Unitful.Quantity{T, 𝐓, U}, Unitful.Level{L, S, Unitful.Quantity{T, 𝐓, U}} where {L, S}} where {T, U}, SimpleScenario, Union{Unitful.Quantity{T, 𝐓, U}, Unitful.Level{L, S, Unitful.Quantity{T, 𝐓, U}} where {L, S}} where {T, U}}","page":"API","text":"runscenario!(eco::Ecosystem, timestep::Unitful.Time, scenario::S, currentstep::Unitful.Time) where S <: AbstractScenario\n\nThis function runs any scenario type for one timestep.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.runscenario!"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.simplehabitat-Tuple{Union{Float64, Unitful.Quantity{Float64}}, Tuple{Int64, Int64}, Unitful.Quantity{Float64}, Union{Unitful.Quantity{Float64, 𝐋^2, U}, Unitful.Level{L, S, Unitful.Quantity{Float64, 𝐋^2, U}} where {L, S}} where U, Matrix{Bool}}","page":"API","text":"simplehabitat(val::Union{Float64, Unitful.Quantity{Float64}},\n    dimension::Tuple{Int64, Int64}, maxsupply::Float64, area::Unitful.Area{Float64},\n    active::Matrix{Bool})\n\nCreate a simple ContinuousRegime, SimpleSupply type abiotic environment. It creates a ContinuousRegime filled with a given value, val, dimensions (dimension) and a specified area (area). It also creates a SimpleSupply type filled with the maximum supply value (maxsupply). If a Bool matrix of active grid squares is included, active, this is used, else one is created with all grid cells active.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.simplehabitat"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.simplehabitat-Tuple{Union{Float64, Unitful.Quantity{Float64}}, Tuple{Int64, Int64}, Unitful.Quantity{Float64}, Union{Unitful.Quantity{Float64, 𝐋^2, U}, Unitful.Level{L, S, Unitful.Quantity{Float64, 𝐋^2, U}} where {L, S}} where U}","page":"API","text":"simplehabitat(val::Union{Float64, Unitful.Quantity{Float64}},\n    dimension::Tuple{Int64, Int64}, maxsupply::Float64, area::Unitful.Area{Float64},\n    active::Matrix{Bool})\n\nCreate a simple ContinuousRegime, SimpleSupply type abiotic environment. It creates a ContinuousRegime filled with a given value, val, dimensions (dimension) and a specified area (area). It also creates a SimpleSupply type filled with the maximum supply value (maxsupply). If a Bool matrix of active grid squares is included, active, this is used, else one is created with all grid cells active.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.simplehabitat"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.simplenichehabitat-Tuple{Int64, Tuple, Unitful.Quantity{Float64}, Union{Unitful.Quantity{Float64, 𝐋^2, U}, Unitful.Level{L, S, Unitful.Quantity{Float64, 𝐋^2, U}} where {L, S}} where U, Matrix{Bool}}","page":"API","text":"simplenichehabitat(numniches::Int64, dimension::Tuple,\n                    maxsupply::Unitful.Quantity{Float64}, area::Unitful.Area{Float64},\n                    active::Matrix{Bool})\n\nCreate a simple DiscreteRegime, SimpleSupply type abiotic environment. Given a number of niche types numniches, it creates a DiscreteRegime environment with dimensions dimension and a specified area area. It also creates a SimpleSupply type filled with the maximum supply value maxsupply. If a Bool matrix of active grid squares is included, active, this is used, else one is created with all grid cells active.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.simplenichehabitat"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.simplenichehabitat-Tuple{Int64, Tuple, Unitful.Quantity{Float64}, Union{Unitful.Quantity{Float64, 𝐋^2, U}, Unitful.Level{L, S, Unitful.Quantity{Float64, 𝐋^2, U}} where {L, S}} where U}","page":"API","text":"simplenichehabitat(numniches::Int64, dimension::Tuple,\n                    maxsupply::Unitful.Quantity{Float64}, area::Unitful.Area{Float64},\n                    active::Matrix{Bool})\n\nCreate a simple DiscreteRegime, SimpleSupply type abiotic environment. Given a number of niche types numniches, it creates a DiscreteRegime environment with dimensions dimension and a specified area area. It also creates a SimpleSupply type filled with the maximum supply value maxsupply. If a Bool matrix of active grid squares is included, active, this is used, else one is created with all grid cells active.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.simplenichehabitat"},{"category":"function","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.simpleregime","page":"API","text":"simpleregime(val::Float64, size::Unitful.Length, dim::Tuple{Int64, Int64},\naxis::Type{<:NicheAxis} = Unclassified)\n\nCreate a dimensionless ContinuousRegime filled with val. Its update rule comes from axis via dynamics(axis).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.simpleregime"},{"category":"function","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.simpleregime-2","page":"API","text":"simpleregime(val::Unitful.Quantity, size::Unitful.Length,\ndim::Tuple{Int64, Int64}, axis::Type{<:NicheAxis} = Unclassified)\n\nCreate a ContinuousRegime regime of dimension dim, with cell size and filled value, val, on niche axis axis.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.simpleregime"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.simulate!-Tuple{CachedEcosystem, Union{Unitful.Quantity{T, 𝐓, U}, Unitful.Level{L, S, Unitful.Quantity{T, 𝐓, U}} where {L, S}} where {T, U}, Union{Unitful.Quantity{T, 𝐓, U}, Unitful.Level{L, S, Unitful.Quantity{T, 𝐓, U}} where {L, S}} where {T, U}}","page":"API","text":"simulate!(cache::CachedEcosystem, srt::Unitful.Time, timestep::Unitful.Time)\n\nRun a cached ecosystem, cache at a specified timepoint, srt, for a particular timestep, timestep.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.simulate!"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.simulate!-Tuple{EcoSISTEM.AbstractEcosystem, Union{Unitful.Quantity{T, 𝐓, U}, Unitful.Level{L, S, Unitful.Quantity{T, 𝐓, U}} where {L, S}} where {T, U}, Union{Unitful.Quantity{T, 𝐓, U}, Unitful.Level{L, S, Unitful.Quantity{T, 𝐓, U}} where {L, S}} where {T, U}}","page":"API","text":"simulate!(eco::AbstractEcosystem, times::Unitful.Time, timestep::Unitful.Time)\n\nRun an ecosystem, eco for a specified length of time, times, for a particular timestep, timestep.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.simulate!"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.simulate!-Tuple{Ecosystem, Union{Unitful.Quantity{T, 𝐓, U}, Unitful.Level{L, S, Unitful.Quantity{T, 𝐓, U}} where {L, S}} where {T, U}, Union{Unitful.Quantity{T, 𝐓, U}, Unitful.Level{L, S, Unitful.Quantity{T, 𝐓, U}} where {L, S}} where {T, U}, Union{Unitful.Quantity{T, 𝐓, U}, Unitful.Level{L, S, Unitful.Quantity{T, 𝐓, U}} where {L, S}} where {T, U}, String, String}","page":"API","text":"simulate!(eco::Ecosystem, times::Unitful.Time, timestep::Unitful.Time,\n          cacheInterval::Unitful.Time, cacheFolder::String,\n          scenario_name::String)\n\nRun an ecosystem, eco for specified length of times, duration, for a particular timestep, 'timestep'. A cache interval and folder/file name are specified for saving output.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.simulate!"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.simulate_action!-Union{Tuple{F}, Tuple{F, EcoSISTEM.AbstractEcosystem, Union{Unitful.Quantity{T, 𝐓, U}, Unitful.Level{L, S, Unitful.Quantity{T, 𝐓, U}} where {L, S}} where {T, U}, Union{Unitful.Quantity{T, 𝐓, U}, Unitful.Level{L, S, Unitful.Quantity{T, 𝐓, U}} where {L, S}} where {T, U}, Union{Unitful.Quantity{T, 𝐓, U}, Unitful.Level{L, S, Unitful.Quantity{T, 𝐓, U}} where {L, S}} where {T, U}}} where F<:Function","page":"API","text":"simulate_action!(action!::Function, eco::AbstractEcosystem, times::Unitful.Time,\n                 interval::Unitful.Time, timestep::Unitful.Time;\n                 scenario = nothing, offset = false)\n\nRun an ecosystem eco up to time times in steps of timestep, calling the user-supplied action! at regular intervals so that any periodic task can be performed as the simulation proceeds — recording a quantity, logging progress, applying a management intervention, checking a stopping condition, and so on. This is the general engine behind the simulate_record! and simulate_record_diversity! recorders; use it directly when you want to do something they do not.\n\nAt each step the ecosystem is advanced with update! and, if a scenario is given, modified with runscenario! (e.g. to remove regime or change climate). Whenever the elapsed time falls on a multiple of interval, action!(counting) is called, where counting is the 1-based index of that occurrence (handy as a storage slot when the action is recording); interval must be a whole multiple of timestep. Anything the action needs to read or update — the ecosystem, an output array, an external counter — is captured by the closure, typically written as a do block:\n\ntotals = zeros(Int, length((0s):interval:times))\nsimulate_action!(eco, times, interval, timestep) do counting\n    totals[counting] = sum(eco.abundances.matrix)\nend\n\noffset shifts the action grid to start at timestep rather than 0, which drops the first occurrence (one fewer action in total). Use it to make the number of actions match a pre-allocated array (such as one from generate_storage); the built-in diversity recorders pass offset = iseven(size(storage, 3)).\n\nReturns the ecosystem eco, now advanced to times.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.simulate_action!"},{"category":"function","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.simulate_record!","page":"API","text":"simulate_record!(storage::AbstractArray, eco::Ecosystem, times::Unitful.Time,\n     interval::Unitful.Time, timestep::Unitful.Time)\nsimulate_record!(storage::AbstractArray, eco::Ecosystem, times::Unitful.Time,\n     interval::Unitful.Time, timestep::Unitful.Time, scenario::AbstractScenario)\n\nRun an ecosystem, eco for a specified length of time, times, for a particular timestep, timestep, recording abundances into storage at each time interval interval. If a scenario is given, it is also run at each timestep to modify the ecosystem, allowing simulation of events such as regime loss or climate change.\n\nPre-allocate storage with generate_storage(eco, ntimes, reps), where ntimes = length((0s):interval:times) is the number of recordings.\n\nTo record diversity rather than raw abundances, see simulate_record_diversity!; to perform an arbitrary action at regular intervals via a callback, see simulate_action!.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.simulate_record!"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.simulate_record_diversity!-Union{Tuple{F}, Tuple{AbstractArray, Ecosystem, Union{Unitful.Quantity{T, 𝐓, U}, Unitful.Level{L, S, Unitful.Quantity{T, 𝐓, U}} where {L, S}} where {T, U}, Union{Unitful.Quantity{T, 𝐓, U}, Unitful.Level{L, S, Unitful.Quantity{T, 𝐓, U}} where {L, S}} where {T, U}, Union{Unitful.Quantity{T, 𝐓, U}, Unitful.Level{L, S, Unitful.Quantity{T, 𝐓, U}} where {L, S}} where {T, U}, SimpleScenario, F, Vector{Float64}}} where F<:Function","page":"API","text":"simulate_record_diversity!(storage, eco, times, interval, timestep,\n                           divfun, qs::Vector{Float64})\nsimulate_record_diversity!(storage, eco, times, interval, timestep,\n                           scenario::SimpleScenario, divfun, qs::Vector{Float64})\nsimulate_record_diversity!(storage, storage2, eco, times, interval, timestep,\n                           qs::Vector{Float64})\nsimulate_record_diversity!(storage, eco, times, interval, timestep,\n                           divfuns::Array{Function}, q::Float64)\nsimulate_record_diversity!(storage, eco, times, interval, timestep,\n                           scenario::SimpleScenario, divfuns::Vector{Function},\n                           q::Float64)\n\nRun an ecosystem eco up to times in steps of timestep, recording diversity into storage (and, for the alpha/beta/gamma form, storage2) every interval, which must be a whole multiple of timestep. These are all thin wrappers over simulate_action! — see it for the recording mechanics — and differ only in what diversity they record:\n\ndivfun, qs — a single diversity function divfun (which returns a DataFrame with a :diversity column) evaluated over the diversity orders qs, reshaped into storage;\nstorage, storage2, …, qs — normalised alpha, normalised beta and gamma diversity over qs; subcommunity-level values are written to storage (gridSize × 3 × timepoints × qs) and metacommunity-level values to storage2 (3 × timepoints × qs);\ndivfuns, q — several diversity functions at a single diversity order q, one per column of storage.\n\nThe scenario::SimpleScenario variants additionally apply scenario at each timestep to modify the ecosystem (e.g. removal of regime patches).\n\nFor the divfun/divfuns forms, pre-allocate storage with generate_storage(eco, ncols, ntimes, reps), where ncols is length(qs) (or length(divfuns)) and ntimes = length((0s):interval:times).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.simulate_record_diversity!"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.sorenson-Tuple{Ecosystem, Vector{Float64}}","page":"API","text":"sorenson(eco::Ecosystem, qs::Vector{Float64})\n\nCalculate the Sorenson similarity for the entire ecosystem.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.sorenson"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.species_blocksize-Tuple{}","page":"API","text":"species_blocksize()\n\nNumber of species iterated together as a contiguous inner block in update!, chosen so one block spans a CPU cache line (cachelinesize ÷ sizeof(Int)).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.species_blocksize"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.suitability-Tuple{EcoSISTEM.AbstractEcosystem, Int64, Int64}","page":"API","text":"suitability(eco::AbstractEcosystem, pos::Int64, sp::Int64)\n\nCalculate nichefit between the current environment and a species' particular trait.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.suitability"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.supplytype-Tuple{NicheAxis}","page":"API","text":"supplytype(::NicheAxis)\n\nThe AbstractSupply concrete type for this axis when used as a Resource resource, or nothing if the axis is not a consumable resource (so it errors clearly rather than silently guessing one if a supply is nonetheless requested).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.supplytype"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.supplyupdate!-Tuple{EcoSISTEM.AbstractEcosystem, Union{Unitful.Quantity{T, 𝐓, U}, Unitful.Level{L, S, Unitful.Quantity{T, 𝐓, U}} where {L, S}} where {T, U}}","page":"API","text":"supplyupdate!(eco::AbstractEcosystem, timestep::Unitful.Time)\n\nUpdate the supply of an ecosystem for one timestep.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.supplyupdate!"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.tematch-Tuple{SpeciesList, EcoSISTEM.AbstractHabitat}","page":"API","text":"tematch(sppl::SpeciesList, habitat::AbstractHabitat)\n\nCheck that the types of a tolerance list and regime list are the same for a species list (sppl) and abiotic environment (habitat).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.tematch"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.tempgrad-Tuple{Union{Unitful.Quantity{Float64, 𝚯, U}, Unitful.Level{L, S, Unitful.Quantity{Float64, 𝚯, U}} where {L, S}} where U, Union{Unitful.Quantity{Float64, 𝚯, U}, Unitful.Level{L, S, Unitful.Quantity{Float64, 𝚯, U}} where {L, S}} where U, Union{Unitful.Quantity{Float64, 𝐋, U}, Unitful.Level{L, S, Unitful.Quantity{Float64, 𝐋, U}} where {L, S}} where U, Tuple{Int64, Int64}, Unitful.Quantity{Float64, 𝚯 𝐓^-1}}","page":"API","text":"tempgrad(minT::Unitful.Temperature{Float64}, maxT::Unitful.Temperature{Float64},\n  size::Unitful.Length{Float64},\n  dim::Tuple{Int64, Int64}, rate::Quantity{Float64, 𝚯*𝐓^-1})\n\nCreate a ContinuousRegime regime with a temperature gradient.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.tempgrad"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.tempgradhabitat-Tuple{Union{Unitful.Quantity{Float64, 𝚯, U}, Unitful.Level{L, S, Unitful.Quantity{Float64, 𝚯, U}} where {L, S}} where U, Union{Unitful.Quantity{Float64, 𝚯, U}, Unitful.Level{L, S, Unitful.Quantity{Float64, 𝚯, U}} where {L, S}} where U, Tuple{Int64, Int64}, Unitful.Quantity{Float64}, Union{Unitful.Quantity{Float64, 𝐋^2, U}, Unitful.Level{L, S, Unitful.Quantity{Float64, 𝐋^2, U}} where {L, S}} where U, Unitful.Quantity{Float64, 𝚯 𝐓^-1}, Matrix{Bool}}","page":"API","text":"tempgradhabitat(minT::Unitful.Temperature{Float64},\n  maxT::Unitful.Temperature{Float64},\n  dimension::Tuple{Int64, Int64}, maxsupply::Unitful.Quantity{Float64},\n  area::Unitful.Area{Float64}, rate::Quantity{Float64, 𝚯*𝐓^-1},\n  active::Matrix{Bool})\n\nCreate a temperature gradient ContinuousRegime, SimpleSupply type abiotic environment. Given a minT and maxT temperature, it generates a gradient from minimum at the bottom to maximum at the top. It creates a ContinuousRegime environment with dimensions dimension and a specified area area. It also creates a SimpleSupply type filled with the maximum supply value maxsupply. The rate of temperature change is specified using the parameter rate. If a Bool matrix of active grid squares is included, active, this is used, else one is created with all grid cells active.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.tempgradhabitat"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.tempgradhabitat-Tuple{Union{Unitful.Quantity{Float64, 𝚯, U}, Unitful.Level{L, S, Unitful.Quantity{Float64, 𝚯, U}} where {L, S}} where U, Union{Unitful.Quantity{Float64, 𝚯, U}, Unitful.Level{L, S, Unitful.Quantity{Float64, 𝚯, U}} where {L, S}} where U, Tuple{Int64, Int64}, Unitful.Quantity{Float64}, Union{Unitful.Quantity{Float64, 𝐋^2, U}, Unitful.Level{L, S, Unitful.Quantity{Float64, 𝐋^2, U}} where {L, S}} where U, Unitful.Quantity{Float64, 𝚯 𝐓^-1}}","page":"API","text":"tempgradhabitat(minT::Unitful.Temperature{Float64},\n  maxT::Unitful.Temperature{Float64},\n  dimension::Tuple{Int64, Int64}, maxsupply::Unitful.Quantity{Float64},\n  area::Unitful.Area{Float64}, rate::Quantity{Float64, 𝚯*𝐓^-1},\n  active::Matrix{Bool})\n\nCreate a temperature gradient ContinuousRegime, SimpleSupply type abiotic environment. Given a minT and maxT temperature, it generates a gradient from minimum at the bottom to maximum at the top. It creates a ContinuousRegime environment with dimensions dimension and a specified area area. It also creates a SimpleSupply type filled with the maximum supply value maxsupply. The rate of temperature change is specified using the parameter rate. If a Bool matrix of active grid squares is included, active, this is used, else one is created with all grid cells active.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.tempgradhabitat"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.tolerancepopulate!-Union{Tuple{R}, Tuple{AB}, Tuple{GridLandscape, SpeciesList, AB, R, Vector{Random.Xoshiro}}} where {AB<:EcoSISTEM.AbstractHabitat, R<:EcoSISTEM.AbstractNicheFit}","page":"API","text":"tolerancepopulate!(ml::GridLandscape, spplist::SpeciesList, habitat::AbstractHabitat,\n               nichefit::AbstractNicheFit, rngs::Vector{Random.Xoshiro})\n\nPopulate the grid landscape ml by scattering each species' total abundance (taken from spplist.abun) across the grid cells with probability proportional to how well the species tolerances match each cell's environment, as scored by the trait nichefit nichefit applied to spplist.tolerance and habitat.regime. Where a species matches no cell the distribution falls back to uniform. Only native species (those flagged in spplist.native) are placed; non-native species are left empty.\n\nThis is the trait-based counterpart of populate!, which instead weights cells by their available resource supply.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.tolerancepopulate!"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.tolerancerepopulate!-Tuple{Ecosystem}","page":"API","text":"tolerancerepopulate!(eco::Ecosystem)\n\nRepopulate an ecosystem eco according to how well species tolerances match their environment, redistributing the total abundance across species at random.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.tolerancerepopulate!"},{"category":"function","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.unziptemp","page":"API","text":"EcoSISTEM.unziptemp(path::String)\n\nHelper function for the FAIR Data Pipeline to unzip files that are stored as zips to a temporary folder.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.unziptemp"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.update!-Tuple{EcoSISTEM.AbstractEcosystem, Union{Unitful.Quantity{T, 𝐓, U}, Unitful.Level{L, S, Unitful.Quantity{T, 𝐓, U}} where {L, S}} where {T, U}}","page":"API","text":"update!(eco::AbstractEcosystem, timestep::Unitful.Time)\n\nDispatch function that selects the appropriate threaded implementation of update! based on the number of available threads.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.update!"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.update!-Tuple{Ecosystem, Union{Unitful.Quantity{T, 𝐓, U}, Unitful.Level{L, S, Unitful.Quantity{T, 𝐓, U}} where {L, S}} where {T, U}}","page":"API","text":"update!(eco::Ecosystem, timestep::Unitful.Time)\n\nUpdate an ecosystem's abundances and environment for one timestep.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.update!"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.update_resource_usage!-Union{Tuple{EcoSISTEM.AbstractEcosystem{A, SpeciesList{TL, DM, B, C, D}, E}}, Tuple{DM}, Tuple{TL}, Tuple{E}, Tuple{D}, Tuple{C}, Tuple{B}, Tuple{A}} where {A, B, C, D, E, TL, DM<:EcoSISTEM.Abstract1Demand}","page":"API","text":"update_resource_usage!(eco::Ecosystem)\n\nCalculate how much resource has been used up by the current species in each grid square in the ecosystem, eco. This function is parameterised on whether the species have one type of resource demand or two.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.update_resource_usage!"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.updatesimulation!-Tuple{CachedEcosystem, Union{Unitful.Quantity{T, 𝐓, U}, Unitful.Level{L, S, Unitful.Quantity{T, 𝐓, U}} where {L, S}} where {T, U}}","page":"API","text":"updatesimulation!(cache::CachedEcosystem, tm::Unitful.Time)\n\nTrigger the computation and caching of ecosystem abundances at timepoint tm in a CachedEcosystem.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.updatesimulation!"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.worldclimhabitat-Tuple{EcoSISTEM.ClimatePref.ClimateRaster{RasterDataSources.WorldClim{RasterDataSources.Climate}}, Unitful.Quantity{Float64}, Union{Unitful.Quantity{Float64, 𝐋^2, U}, Unitful.Level{L, S, Unitful.Quantity{Float64, 𝐋^2, U}} where {L, S}} where U, Matrix{Bool}}","page":"API","text":"worldclimhabitat(worldclim::ClimateRaster{WorldClim{Climate}}, maxsupply::Unitful.Quantity{Float64},\n  area::Unitful.Area{Float64}, active::Matrix{Bool})\n\nAs worldclimhabitat with an explicit active matrix of grid squares, rather than inferring active cells from NaN values in the Worldclim data.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.worldclimhabitat"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.worldclimhabitat-Tuple{EcoSISTEM.ClimatePref.ClimateRaster{RasterDataSources.WorldClim{RasterDataSources.Climate}}, Unitful.Quantity{Float64}, Union{Unitful.Quantity{Float64, 𝐋^2, U}, Unitful.Level{L, S, Unitful.Quantity{Float64, 𝐋^2, U}} where {L, S}} where U}","page":"API","text":"worldclimhabitat(worldclim::ClimateRaster{WorldClim{Climate}}, maxsupply::Unitful.Quantity{Float64},      area::Unitful.Area{Float64})\n\nCreate a ContinuousTimeRegime, SimpleSupply type abiotic environment from a Worldclim type climate. It either creates a SimpleSupply type filled with the maximum supply value maxsupply or uses a provided supply of type SolarTimeSupply. If a Bool matrix of active grid squares is included, active, this is used, otherwise all grid cells are considered active.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.worldclimhabitat"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.worldclimhabitat-Union{Tuple{B}, Tuple{EcoSISTEM.ClimatePref.ClimateRaster{RasterDataSources.WorldClim{RasterDataSources.Climate}}, B, Matrix{Bool}}} where B<:(ContinuousLayer{EcoSISTEM.Resource, A, V, Arr} where {A, V, Arr<:AbstractArray{V, 3}})","page":"API","text":"worldclimhabitat(worldclim::ClimateRaster{WorldClim{Climate}}, supply::B, active::Matrix{Bool}) where B <: AbstractTimeSupply\n\nAs worldclimhabitat but accepts a pre-constructed AbstractTimeSupply object supply rather than computing a supply from a maximum value.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.worldclimhabitat"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.ClimatePref.AbstractClimate","page":"API","text":"AbstractClimate\n\nAbstract supertype of all climate data.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.ClimatePref.AbstractClimate"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.ClimatePref.AxisNode","page":"API","text":"AxisNode\n\nOne node of the layeraxes niche-axis tree: the axis type itself, the names of shipped layers that use it directly (an abstract grouping axis never carries a layer itself — only a concrete leaf does, so this is empty for every non-leaf node), and its children — the axis types immediately below it, each an AxisNode built the same way, recursively down to the concrete leaves.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.ClimatePref.AxisNode"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.ClimatePref.CERA","page":"API","text":"CERA <: AbstractClimate\n\nType that houses data extracted from CERA-20C raster files.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.ClimatePref.CERA"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.ClimatePref.CRUTS","page":"API","text":"CRUTS <: AbstractClimate\n\nType that houses data extracted from CRUTS raster files.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.ClimatePref.CRUTS"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.ClimatePref.ClimateRaster","page":"API","text":"ClimateRaster{<:RDS.RasterDataSource, <: AxisArray} <: AbstractClimate\n\nType for climate data derived from RasterDataSources.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.ClimatePref.ClimateRaster"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.ClimatePref.ERA","page":"API","text":"ERA <: AbstractClimate\n\nType that houses data extracted from ERA raster files.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.ClimatePref.ERA"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.ClimatePref.LayerRecord","page":"API","text":"LayerRecord\n\nA single layer's catalogue entry: its dataset (the table basename, e.g. :BioClim), code aliases (the ;-separated Code, e.g. [\"1\", \"bio1\"]), name, definition, physical unit (NoUnits if dimensionless), axis (a NicheAxis type, or nothing if unclassified), the sources that provide it (the full list of supporting RasterDataSources), the numlayers the code expands to, and its temporal native reporting period — a genuine Unitful.Units time unit (day/month/quarter/year), or nothing for a static/non-time-varying value. Returned by layerinfo / layersbyaxis.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.ClimatePref.LayerRecord"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.ClimatePref.Reference","page":"API","text":"Reference <: AbstractClimate\n\nType that houses a reference data array.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.ClimatePref.Reference"},{"category":"function","location":"api/#Base.read","page":"API","text":"read(T::Type{<:RasterDataSource}, layers = RasterDataSources.layers(T);\n     cut = nothing, scale, fn, kw...)\n\nDownload (via getraster) and read a RasterDataSources layer set into a ClimateRaster. layers chooses which layers/variables to read (default: all of them). cut, if given, restricts the result to a (lat = a .. b, long = c .. d) box of ° intervals. scale/fn coarsen each raster by an integer block-aggregation factor with reducer fn (source-specific defaults — e.g. EarthEnv{LandCover} is aggregated 10×). Any remaining keywords (e.g. month) pass through to getraster.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Base.read"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.ClimatePref.boundingbox-Tuple{AbstractString}","page":"API","text":"boundingbox(region::AbstractString; islands = false, round = false)\n\nReturn the geographic bounding box of region as a LatLong of ° intervals, ready to pass as the cut keyword to read and the other raster readers. Boxes are read from the shipped data/bounding_boxes.csv table. islands = true selects the island-inclusive extent (the table's Islands coverage) instead of the mainland one. round, when given a degree step (e.g. round = 5°), snaps the box outwards to the nearest multiple of that step so the rounded box fully contains the exact one; the default false leaves it unrounded.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.ClimatePref.boundingbox"},{"category":"function","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.ClimatePref.convert_coords","page":"API","text":"convert_coords(i::Int64, width::Int64)\nconvert_coords(x::Int64, y::Int64, width::Int64)\n\nFunction to convert coordinates from two-dimensional (x,y) format to one dimension (i), or vice versa, using the width of the grid. This function can also be applied to arrays of coordinates.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.ClimatePref.convert_coords"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.ClimatePref.create_reference-Tuple{Float64}","page":"API","text":"create_reference(gridsize::Float64)\n\nFunction to create a reference grid array of type Reference.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.ClimatePref.create_reference"},{"category":"function","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.ClimatePref.downresolution","page":"API","text":"downresolution(data::Union{ERA, ClimateRaster{WorldClim{BioClim}, <: AxisArray}}, rescale::Int64; fn)\n\nFunction to decrease the resolution of a climate dataset, by a factor, rescale, and aggregation function, fn. The aggregation function has a default setting of taking the mean value.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.ClimatePref.downresolution"},{"category":"function","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.ClimatePref.downresolution!","page":"API","text":"downresolution!(resized_array::Matrix{T}, array::Matrix{T}, rescale::Int64, fn)\ndownresolution!(resized_array::Array{T, 3}, array::Matrix{T}, dim::Int64, rescale::Int64, fn)\n\nFunction to decrease the resolution of a climate dataset in place, by a factor, rescale, and aggregation function, fn. The aggregation function has a default setting of taking the mean value.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.ClimatePref.downresolution!"},{"category":"function","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.ClimatePref.extractvalues","page":"API","text":"extractvalues(lat, long, dat::AbstractClimate, slice = :; year = nothing)\nextractvalues(lats, longs, dat::AbstractClimate, slice = :; year = nothing)\nextractvalues(loc::LatLong, dat::AbstractClimate, slice = :; year = nothing)\nextractvalues(locs, dat::AbstractClimate, slice = :; year = nothing)\n\nExtract the value(s) at the grid cell(s) containing (lat, long) from a climate dataset.\n\nA location is a LatLong point; pass a single one, a vector of them, or the equivalent separate lat/long scalars or lats/longs vectors (which build the LatLongs and forward). slice chooses along the non-spatial third axis — a month (Unitful.Time) or a variable/band index (Int), depending on the dataset — as a single value (one slice), a vector (those slices), or : (all slices, the default); it is ignored for the 2-D Reference. For a dataset with a calendar time axis, the year keyword selects the entries falling within that calendar year — however many exist, none if the year lies outside the data — and slice is then read as month number(s) within the year.\n\nA single location with a single slice returns a scalar; a single location with several/all slices returns a vector; N locations return an N×1 (single slice) or N×M matrix.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.ClimatePref.extractvalues"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.ClimatePref.fitBrownian-Tuple{Phylo.AbstractTree, Vector{F} where F<:AbstractFloat}","page":"API","text":"fitBrownian(tree::AbstractTree, traits::Vector{F}) where F <: AbstractFloat\n\nFit a Brownian motion model of trait evolution to traits measured at the tips of tree. Returns a Brownian object containing the maximum likelihood estimates of the diffusion rate σ² and root state z̄₀, their standard errors, the Hessian, and the log-likelihood.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.ClimatePref.fitBrownian"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.ClimatePref.fitLambda-Tuple{Phylo.AbstractTree, Vector{F} where F<:AbstractFloat}","page":"API","text":"fitLambda(tree::AbstractTree, traits::Vector{F}) where F <: AbstractFloat\n\nFit Pagel's lambda model of trait evolution to traits measured at the tips of tree. Returns a Lambda object containing the maximum likelihood estimates of σ², root state z̄₀, and phylogenetic signal λ, their standard errors, the Hessian, and the log-likelihood.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.ClimatePref.fitLambda"},{"category":"function","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.ClimatePref.layeraxes","page":"API","text":"layeraxes(A::Type{<:NicheAxis} = NicheAxis)\n\nReturn the niche-axis hierarchy at and below A (the whole tree by default) as a nested AxisNode: each node carries the shipped layer names that use its axis directly (only a concrete leaf ever has any — an abstract grouping node's own names is always empty) plus its child axis nodes, recursively down to the concrete leaves. Use it to discover which axes exist and what shipped layers use them, then drill into a group with layersbyaxis.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.ClimatePref.layeraxes"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.ClimatePref.layeraxis-Tuple{Type{<:RasterDataSources.RasterDataSource}, Any}","page":"API","text":"layeraxis(T::Type{<:RasterDataSources.RasterDataSource}, code)\n\nReturn the NicheAxis type declared for layer code of dataset T in its shipped data/ table, or nothing if the Axis cell is blank (or absent). A blank axis is an unclassified layer — documented and unit-bearing, but not modelled as a niche axis; to use it, pass an explicit axis when building the layer.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.ClimatePref.layeraxis"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.ClimatePref.layerinfo-Tuple{Type{<:RasterDataSources.RasterDataSource}, Any}","page":"API","text":"layerinfo(T::Type{<:RasterDataSources.RasterDataSource}, code)\nlayerinfo(code)\n\nReturn the catalogue LayerRecord for a layer, with its name, definition, unit, niche axis and sources. The two-argument form looks up code in dataset T's table (mirrors layerunit(T, code)) and returns one record. The single-argument form (an Integer/Symbol/String code) searches EVERY shipped table and returns a Vector of all matches — the same code can appear in several datasets (e.g. bio1 is in both BioClim and BioClimPlus).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.ClimatePref.layerinfo"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.ClimatePref.layersbyaxis-Tuple{Type{<:NicheAxis}}","page":"API","text":"layersbyaxis(A::Type{<:NicheAxis})\n\nReturn a Vector of LayerRecords for every layer (across all shipped tables) whose axis is A or a concrete leaf beneath it. Passing an abstract group spans all its axes — layersbyaxis(TemperatureAxis) returns every temperature layer, layersbyaxis(Temperature) just that one axis. Printed as a compact list of codes with short summaries.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.ClimatePref.layersbyaxis"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.ClimatePref.layerunit-Tuple{Type{<:RasterDataSources.RasterDataSource}, Any}","page":"API","text":"layerunit(T::Type{<:RasterDataSources.RasterDataSource}, code)\n\nReturn the physical unit of layer code in raster dataset T (e.g. layerunit(WorldClim{BioClim}, 1) is K, layerunit(WorldClim{Climate}, :srad) is kJ m⁻² day⁻¹). Looked up in the dataset's shipped data/ table and parsed with Unitful.uparse; a blank Units cell means dimensionless (NoUnits). code is matched by its string form, so integer layer numbers and Symbol/String keys both work.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.ClimatePref.layerunit"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.ClimatePref.readCERA-Tuple{String, String, String}","page":"API","text":"readCERA(dir::String, file::String, param::String; cut = nothing)\n\nRead variable param from the CERA-20C netCDF files in directory dir whose names contain file — one per decade — and concatenate them along time into a single CERA. The monthly time coordinate for each decade is generated internally; ERA/CERA longitudes are wrapped onto (-180°, 180°]. Built on the single-file three-argument readERA (once per file).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.ClimatePref.readCERA"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.ClimatePref.readCHELSA_monthly-Tuple{String, String}","page":"API","text":"readCHELSA_monthly(dir::String, var_name::String; scale = 1, fn = mean, cut = nothing)\n\nRead every .tif in dir as a monthly time series of variable var_name (optionally coarsened by scale/fn) and return a ClimateRaster{CHELSA{Climate}}.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.ClimatePref.readCHELSA_monthly"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.ClimatePref.readCRUTS-Tuple{String, String}","page":"API","text":"readCRUTS(dir::String, var_name::String; cut = nothing)\n\nRead every .tif in dir as a monthly time series of variable var_name and return a CRUTS. var_name uses the same short codes as WorldClim{Climate}'s shipped layer table (tavg, wind, prec, …), which is where the attached unit comes from — CRU TS has no layer table of its own.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.ClimatePref.readCRUTS"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.ClimatePref.readERA-Tuple{String, String, String, Vector{<:AbstractVector{<:Union{Unitful.Quantity{T, 𝐓, U}, Unitful.Level{L, S, Unitful.Quantity{T, 𝐓, U}} where {L, S}} where {T, U}}}}","page":"API","text":"readERA(dir::String, file::String, param::String,\n        dim::Vector{<:AbstractVector{<:Unitful.Time}}; cut = nothing)\n\nRead variable param from every ERA netCDF file in directory dir whose name contains file, concatenating them along time into one ERA. dim gives the time coordinate per file — a vector of time-vectors, one per matched file (in readdir order). This is the multi-file wrapper over the single-file three-argument method above.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.ClimatePref.readERA"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.ClimatePref.readERA-Tuple{String, String, Vector{<:Union{Unitful.Quantity{T, 𝐓, U}, Unitful.Level{L, S, Unitful.Quantity{T, 𝐓, U}} where {L, S}} where {T, U}}}","page":"API","text":"readERA(file::String, param::String, dim::Vector{<:Unitful.Time}; cut = nothing)\n\nRead variable param from a single ERA netCDF file and return an ERA. dim is the time coordinate attached to the file's layers (one entry per monthly layer); ERA longitudes are wrapped onto (-180°, 180°]. To read and time-concatenate a whole directory of files, use the four-argument method below.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.ClimatePref.readERA"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.ClimatePref.readfile-Tuple{String}","page":"API","text":"readfile(file::String; cut = nothing)\n\nImport a raster file from a path string into an AxisArray. cut, if given, restricts the result to a LatLong box of ° intervals (e.g. from boundingbox).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.ClimatePref.readfile"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.ClimatePref.readworldclim-Tuple{Type{RasterDataSources.WorldClim{RasterDataSources.Climate}}, Any}","page":"API","text":"readworldclim(T::Type{WorldClim{Climate}}, files; cut = nothing)\n\nDeprecated — use read(WorldClim{Climate}, layers; …) instead, which downloads via getraster and reads through the same machinery. Retained to read an already-resolved set of monthly climate raster file paths.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.ClimatePref.readworldclim"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.ClimatePref.searchdir-Tuple{Any, Any}","page":"API","text":"searchdir(path,key)\n\nFunction to search a directory path using a given key string.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.ClimatePref.searchdir"},{"category":"function","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.ClimatePref.upresolution","page":"API","text":"upresolution(data::Union{ERA, ClimateRaster}, rescale::Int64; fn)\n\nFunction to increase the resolution of a climate dataset, by a factor, rescale.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.ClimatePref.upresolution"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#EcoSISTEM.ClimatePref.varcovar-Tuple{Phylo.AbstractTree}","page":"API","text":"varcovar(tree::AbstractTree)\n\nCompute the phylogenetic variance-covariance matrix from the branch lengths of tree. The diagonal entries are the root-to-tip distances and the off-diagonal entries are the shared root-to-ancestor distances between pairs of tips.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"EcoSISTEM.ClimatePref.varcovar"},{"category":"section","location":"diversity/#Integration-with-Diversity.jl","page":"Diversity","text":"EcoSISTEM is integrated with the Diversity package, so that diversity measures can be calculated directly on ecosystems.\n\nSee Basics for more information on setting up an Ecosystem.\n\nusing Diversity\n# Subcommunity measures\nnorm_sub_alpha(eco, 1.0)\n# Or metacommunity measures\nnorm_meta_alpha(eco, 1.0)\n# Or multiple values of q\nnorm_sub_beta(eco, 0.0:3.0)","title":"Integration with Diversity.jl"},{"category":"section","location":"pipeline/#Data-pipeline","page":"Data Pipeline","text":"DataPipeline.jl is a Julia package that provides functionality for the FAIR Data Pipeline. The pipeline is intended to enable tracking of provenance of FAIR (findable, accessible, interoperable and reusable) data. We use it in examples under the pipeline folder for a run of a single species in Africa. \n\nSee here for details on what to install to set up the Data Pipeline. Once installed, the workflow is to initialise the pipeline in the repository, pull in the external data needed for the simulation (as described in the AfricaRun.yaml) and run the simulation. The output is also described in the AfricaRun.yaml, which is produced from the corresponding run file AfricaRun.jl. The output and provenance can then be pushed back to the online data registry to be inspected further.\n\n## Initialise the data pipeline in the git repository\nfair init\n# Pull in any external data described in the yaml\nfair pull .\\examples\\pipeline\\AfricaRun.yaml\n# Run the simulation described in the yaml\nfair run .\\examples\\pipeline\\AfricaRun.yaml\n# Stage the code run using the unique identifier\nfair add <code-run>\n# Push the run and corresponding metadata back to the online registry\nfair push","title":"Data pipeline"},{"category":"section","location":"examples/#Examples","page":"Examples","text":"Here we describe several properties that the model ecosystem should be able to recreate, namely:\n\nSpecies are more abundant when more resources are available to them.\nSpecies' abundances scale with area and are invariant to grid size.\nSpecies with larger average dispersal distances can move further and faster across the landscape.\nSpecies have a competitive advantage when their niche preference is close to that of the climate.\nSpecialist species with a narrow niche width have a competitive advantage over generalists with a broad niche width, for the same niche preference.\nLarge numbers of species are sustained over large areas.\n\nWhat follows are several examples of this operating in practice.\n\nusing EcoSISTEM\nusing EcoSISTEM.Units\nusing Unitful\nusing Unitful.DefaultSymbols\nusing Diversity\nusing JLD2\nusing OnlineStats\nusing Plots\nusing Distributions\nusing Diversity\nplotlyjs()","title":"Examples"},{"category":"section","location":"examples/#1.-Different-niche-preferences-and-widths","page":"Examples","text":"Here we compare the abundances of species with different temperature preferences and tolerances. On a small patch,we explored the abundance of species given different niche preferences, with all other parameters kept equal. We found that species with niche preference nearer to the 25°C optimum were more abundant, when all species were given the same niche widths. Additionally, when all species had a preference for the 25°C climate and a range of niche widths, those with broader niche widths (generalists) were less abundant than species with narrow (specialists). If the temperature in the ecosystem was then increased by 1°C, those with the narrowest niches went extinct, and the generalists became more abundant, with a preference for those with a niche width of around 1°C as we would expect.\n\nnumSpecies = 100; grd = (10,10); demand=(450000.0kJ/m^2, 192.0nm/m^2);\nindividuals = 100_000_000; area = 100.0*km^2;\ntotalK = (4.5e11kJ/km^2, 192.0mm/km^2)\n\nhabitat1 = simplehabitat(298.0K, grd, totalK[1], area)\nhabitat2 = simplehabitat(298.0K, grd, totalK[2], area)\nsupply = SupplyCollection2(habitat1.supply, habitat2.supply)\nhabitat = GridHabitat{typeof(habitat1.regime), typeof(supply)}(habitat1.regime, habitat1.active, supply, habitat1.names)\n\nvars = fill(2.0, numSpecies) .* K\nopts = 298.0K .+ vars .* range(-3, stop = 3, length = numSpecies)\n\nav_dist = fill(2.4, numSpecies) .* km\nkernel = GaussianKernel.(av_dist, 10e-10)\n\ndeath = 0.15/ year\nbirth = death\nl = 1.0\ns = 0.1\nboost = 1.0\n\nsize_mean = 1.0m^2\n# Set up how much energy each species consumes\nresource_vec1 = SolarDemand(fill(demand[1] * size_mean, numSpecies))\nresource_vec2 = WaterDemand(fill(demand[2] * size_mean, numSpecies))\n\nresource_vec = DemandCollection2(resource_vec1, resource_vec2)\nparam = EqualPop(birth, death, l, s , boost)\n\n# Create ecosystem\n\nmovement = BirthOnlyMovement(kernel, Torus())\n\ntraits = GaussTrait(opts, vars)\nnative = fill(true, numSpecies)\nabun = rand(Multinomial(individuals, numSpecies))\nsppl = SpeciesList(numSpecies, traits, abun, resource_vec,\n    movement, param, native)\nnichefit = Gauss{typeof(first(opts))}()\neco = Ecosystem(sppl, habitat, nichefit)\n\ntimes = 10years; timestep = 1month\nlensim = length(0month:timestep:times)\n\nsimulate!(eco, times, timestep)\nendabun = eco.abundances.matrix\ntemps = map(eachindex(opts)) do i\n    repeat([opts[i]], endabun[i])\nend\n\ntemps = vcat(temps...)\nedges = collect(292.0:1:304) .* K\nh = Hist(edges)\nfit!(h, temps)\nbar(ustrip.(uconvert.(°C, edges)), h.counts,\ngrid = false, xlab = \"Temperature preference (°C)\",\nylab = \"Abundance\",\nguidefontsize = 16, tickfontsize= 16, size = (1200, 1000),\ntitlefontsize = 16, title = \"A\", titleloc = :left,\nmargin = 10.0*Plots.mm, label = \"\", layout = (@layout[a; b c]))\n\n## DIFFERENT VARS ##\n\nnumSpecies = 100; grd = (10,10); demand=(450000.0kJ/m^2, 192.0nm/m^2);\nindividuals = 100_000_000; area = 100.0*km^2;\ntotalK = (4.5e11kJ/km^2, 192.0mm/km^2)\n\nhabitat1 = simplehabitat(298.0K, grd, totalK[1], area)\nhabitat2 = simplehabitat(298.0K, grd, totalK[2], area)\nsupply = SupplyCollection2(habitat1.supply, habitat2.supply)\nhabitat = GridHabitat{typeof(habitat1.regime), typeof(supply)}(habitat1.regime, habitat1.active, supply, habitat1.names)\n\nvars = range(0.0001, stop = 5, length = numSpecies) .* K\nopts = fill(298.0K, numSpecies)\n\nav_dist = fill(2.4, numSpecies) .* km\nkernel = GaussianKernel.(av_dist, 10e-10)\n\ndeath = 0.15/ year\nbirth = death\nl = 1.0\ns = 0.1\nboost = 1.0\n\nsize_mean = 1.0m^2\n# Set up how much energy each species consumes\nresource_vec1 = SolarDemand(fill(demand[1] * size_mean, numSpecies))\nresource_vec2 = WaterDemand(fill(demand[2] * size_mean, numSpecies))\n\nresource_vec = DemandCollection2(resource_vec1, resource_vec2)\nparam = EqualPop(birth, death, l, s , boost)\n\n# Create ecosystem\n\nmovement = BirthOnlyMovement(kernel, Torus())\n\ntraits = GaussTrait(opts, vars)\nnative = fill(true, numSpecies)\nabun = rand(Multinomial(individuals, numSpecies))\nsppl = SpeciesList(numSpecies, traits, abun, resource_vec,\n    movement, param, native)\nnichefit = Gauss{typeof(first(opts))}()\neco = Ecosystem(sppl, habitat, nichefit)\n\ntimes = 10years; timestep = 1month\nlensim = length(0month:timestep:times)\n\nsimulate!(eco, times, timestep)\nendabun = eco.abundances.matrix\nwidths = map(eachindex(vars)) do i\n    repeat([vars[i]], endabun[i])\nend\nwidths = vcat(widths...)\nedges = collect(0.1:0.2:5) .* K\nh = Hist(edges)\nfit!(h, widths)\nbar!(edges./K, h.counts, grid = false,\nxlab = \"Niche width (°C)\", ylab = \"Abundance\",\nguidefontsize = 16, tickfontsize= 16, titlefontsize = 16,\nmargin = 10.0*Plots.mm, left_margin = 20.0 * Plots.mm, label = \"\",\nsubplot = 2,\ntitle = \"B\", titleloc = :left, ylim = (0, 32_000))\n\n## DIFFERENT VARS MISMATCH ##\nnumSpecies = 100; grd = (10,10); demand=(450000.0kJ/m^2, 192.0nm/m^2);\nindividuals = 100_000_000; area = 100.0*km^2;\ntotalK = (4.5e11kJ/km^2, 192.0mm/km^2)\n\nhabitat1 = simplehabitat(299.0K, grd, totalK[1], area)\nhabitat2 = simplehabitat(299.0K, grd, totalK[2], area)\nsupply = SupplyCollection2(habitat1.supply, habitat2.supply)\nhabitat = GridHabitat{typeof(habitat1.regime), typeof(supply)}(habitat1.regime, habitat1.active, supply, habitat1.names)\n\nvars = range(0.0001, stop = 5, length = numSpecies) .* K\nopts = fill(298.0K, numSpecies)\n\nav_dist = fill(2.4, numSpecies) .* km\nkernel = GaussianKernel.(av_dist, 10e-10)\n\ndeath = 0.15/ year\nbirth = death\nl = 1.0\ns = 0.1\nboost = 1.0\n\nsize_mean = 1.0m^2\n# Set up how much energy each species consumes\nresource_vec1 = SolarDemand(fill(demand[1] * size_mean, numSpecies))\nresource_vec2 = WaterDemand(fill(demand[2] * size_mean, numSpecies))\n\nresource_vec = DemandCollection2(resource_vec1, resource_vec2)\nparam = EqualPop(birth, death, l, s , boost)\n\n# Create ecosystem\n\nmovement = BirthOnlyMovement(kernel, Torus())\n\ntraits = GaussTrait(opts, vars)\nnative = fill(true, numSpecies)\nabun = rand(Multinomial(individuals, numSpecies))\nsppl = SpeciesList(numSpecies, traits, abun, resource_vec,\n    movement, param, native)\nnichefit = Gauss{typeof(first(opts))}()\neco = Ecosystem(sppl, habitat, nichefit)\n\ntimes = 10years; timestep = 1month\nlensim = length(0month:timestep:times)\n\nsimulate!(eco, times, timestep)\nendabun = eco.abundances.matrix\nwidths = map(eachindex(vars)) do i\n    repeat([vars[i]], endabun[i])\nend\nwidths = vcat(widths...)\nedges = collect(0.1:0.2:5) .* K\nh = Hist(edges)\nfit!(h, widths)\nbar!(edges./K, h.counts, grid = false,\nxlab = \"Niche width (°C)\", ylab = \"\",\nguidefontsize = 16, tickfontsize= 16, titlefontsize = 16,\nmargin = 10.0*Plots.mm, label = \"\", subplot = 3,\ntitle = \"C\", titleloc = :left, ylim = (0, 32_000))\n\n(Image: ) Abundance of species across 100km² patch ecosystem with 100 species, (A) with a different temperature preferences and a homogeneous climate of 25°C, (B)  with different niche widths and a temperature preference for 25°C and (C) different niche widths with a shifted homogeneous climate of 26°C.","title":"1. Different niche preferences and widths"},{"category":"section","location":"examples/#2.-Varying-resources,-grid-sizes,-areas-and-number-of-species","page":"Examples","text":"Firstly, we confirmed that abundance depended upon the amount of available resource. Here, we simulated an island ecosystem with two resources, water and sunlight, each on a gradient West to East and South to North, respectively. All species were seeded with the same resource demands and vital rates. Abundance increased in squares with greater amounts of water and sunlight, with some edge effects. Next, we investigated the nichefit between abundance and area size. As expected, ecosystems with greater areas could support more individuals, and these abundances were invariant to the resolution of the grid. We also tested in an ecosystem in which species demographic and dispersal rates and resource demands varied. Under these circumstances, some species not favoured for the conditions go extinct, but most species survive to the end of the simulation.\n\n## MORE ENERGY MORE ABUNDANCE ##\nnumSpecies = 100; grd = (10,10); demand=(450000.0kJ/m^2, 192.0nm/m^2); individuals = 100_000_000; area = 100.0*km^2; totalK = (4.5e11kJ/km^2, 192.0mm/km^2)\n\nhabitat1 = simplehabitat(298.0K, grd, totalK[1], area)\nhabitat2 = simplehabitat(298.0K, grd, totalK[2], area)\nsupply = SupplyCollection2(habitat1.supply, habitat2.supply)\nhabitat = GridHabitat{typeof(habitat1.regime), typeof(supply)}(habitat1.regime, habitat1.active, supply, habitat1.names)\ngsize = size(habitat.supply.one.matrix, 1)\nsol_range = collect(range(0.0kJ, stop = 4.5e11kJ, length = gsize))\n map(1:gsize) do seq\n   habitat.supply.one.matrix[seq, :] .= sol_range[seq]\n end\nhabitat.supply.one.matrix\n\ngsize = size(habitat.supply.two.matrix, 1)\nwater_range = collect(range(0.0mm, stop = 192mm, length = gsize))\nmap(1:gsize) do seq\n    habitat.supply.two.matrix[:, seq] .= water_range[seq]\nend\nhabitat.supply.two.matrix\n\nvars = fill(2.0, numSpecies) .* K\nopts = fill(298.0, numSpecies) .* K\nav_dist = fill(2.4, numSpecies) .* km\nkernel = GaussianKernel.(av_dist, 10e-10)\n\ndeath = 0.15/ year\nbirth = death\nl = 1.0\ns = 0.1\nboost = 1.0\n\nsize_mean = 1.0m^2\n# Set up how much energy each species consumes\nresource_vec1 = SolarDemand(fill(demand[1] * size_mean, numSpecies))\nresource_vec2 = WaterDemand(fill(demand[2] * size_mean, numSpecies))\n\nresource_vec = DemandCollection2(resource_vec1, resource_vec2)\nparam = EqualPop(birth, death, l, s , boost)\n\n# Create ecosystem\n\nmovement = BirthOnlyMovement(kernel, NoBoundary())\n\ntraits = GaussTrait(opts, vars)\nnative = fill(true, numSpecies)\nabun = rand(Multinomial(individuals, numSpecies))\nsppl = SpeciesList(numSpecies, traits, abun, resource_vec,\n    movement, param, native)\nnichefit = Gauss{typeof(first(opts))}()\neco = Ecosystem(sppl, habitat, nichefit)\n\ntimes = 10years; timestep = 1month\nlensim = length(0month:timestep:times)\n\nsimulate!(eco, times, timestep)\nendabun = sum(eco.abundances.matrix, dims = 1)\nendabun = reshape(endabun, 10, 10)\n\nheatmap(sol_range./kJ, water_range./mm, endabun, grid = false,\n xlab = \"Solar energy\", ylab = \"Water\", size = (1600, 1200),\nguidefontsize = 16, tickfontsize= 16, titlefontsize=24,\nmargin = 10.0*Plots.mm, legendfontsize = 16, label = \"\", left_margin = 20.0 * Plots.mm,\nlayout = (@layout [a b; c d]), title = \"A\", titleloc = :left)\n\n\n\n## INVARIANT TO GRID SIZE ##\ntimes = 10years; timestep = 1month\nlensim = length(0month:timestep:times)\nendabuns = zeros(Int64, 4)\ngrids = [1,2,5,10]\nfor i in eachindex(grids)\n    numSpecies = 100; grd = (grids[i],grids[i]); demand=(450000.0kJ/m^2, 192.0nm/m^2);\n    individuals = 100_000_000; area = 100.0*km^2;\n    totalK = (4.5e11kJ/km^2, 192.0mm/km^2)\n\n    habitat1 = simplehabitat(298.0K, grd, totalK[1], area)\n    habitat2 = simplehabitat(298.0K, grd, totalK[2], area)\n    supply = SupplyCollection2(habitat1.supply, habitat2.supply)\n    habitat = GridHabitat{typeof(habitat1.regime), typeof(supply)}(habitat1.regime, habitat1.active, supply, habitat1.names)\n\n    vars = fill(2.0, numSpecies) .* K\n    opts = fill(298.0, numSpecies) .* K\n    av_dist = fill(2.4, numSpecies) .* km\n    kernel = GaussianKernel.(av_dist, 10e-10)\n\n    death = 0.15/ year\n    birth = death\n    l = 1.0\n    s = 0.1\n    boost = 1.0\n\n    size_mean = 1.0m^2\n    # Set up how much energy each species consumes\n    resource_vec1 = SolarDemand(fill(demand[1] * size_mean, numSpecies))\n    resource_vec2 = WaterDemand(fill(demand[2] * size_mean, numSpecies))\n\n    resource_vec = DemandCollection2(resource_vec1, resource_vec2)\n    param = EqualPop(birth, death, l, s , boost)\n\n    # Create ecosystem\n\n    movement = BirthOnlyMovement(kernel, NoBoundary())\n\n    traits = GaussTrait(opts, vars)\n    native = fill(true, numSpecies)\n    abun = rand(Multinomial(individuals, numSpecies))\n    sppl = SpeciesList(numSpecies, traits, abun, resource_vec,\n        movement, param, native)\n    nichefit = Gauss{typeof(first(opts))}()\n    eco = Ecosystem(sppl, habitat, nichefit)\n    simulate!(eco, times, timestep)\n    endabuns[i] = sum(eco.abundances.matrix)\nend\n\nbar!(string.(grids), endabuns,\ngrid = false, xlab = \"Number of grid squares\",\nylab = \"Total abundance\",\nguidefontsize = 16,tickfontsize= 16, titlefontsize=24,\nmargin = 10.0*Plots.mm, label = \"\", left_margin = 20.0 * Plots.mm,\nsubplot = 2, title = \"B\", titleloc = :left)\n\n## ABUNDANCE SCALES WITH AREA ##\ntimes = 10years; timestep = 1month\nlensim = length(0month:timestep:times)\nendabuns = zeros(Int64, 4)\nareas = [10.0,20.0,50.0,100.0]\nfor i in eachindex(areas)\n    numSpecies = 100; grd = (10,10); demand=(450000.0kJ/m^2, 192.0nm/m^2);\n    individuals = 100_000_000; area = areas[i].*km^2;\n    totalK = (4.5e11kJ/km^2, 192.0mm/km^2)\n\n    habitat1 = simplehabitat(298.0K, grd, totalK[1], area)\n    habitat2 = simplehabitat(298.0K, grd, totalK[2], area)\n    supply = SupplyCollection2(habitat1.supply, habitat2.supply)\n    habitat = GridHabitat{typeof(habitat1.regime), typeof(supply)}(habitat1.regime, habitat1.active, supply, habitat1.names)\n\n    vars = fill(2.0, numSpecies) .* K\n    opts = fill(298.0, numSpecies) .* K\n    av_dist = fill(2.4, numSpecies) .* km\n    kernel = GaussianKernel.(av_dist, 10e-10)\n\n    death = 0.15/ year\n    birth = death\n    l = 1.0\n    s = 0.1\n    boost = 1.0\n\n    size_mean = 1.0m^2\n    # Set up how much energy each species consumes\n    resource_vec1 = SolarDemand(fill(demand[1] * size_mean, numSpecies))\n    resource_vec2 = WaterDemand(fill(demand[2] * size_mean, numSpecies))\n\n    resource_vec = DemandCollection2(resource_vec1, resource_vec2)\n    param = EqualPop(birth, death, l, s , boost)\n\n    # Create ecosystem\n\n    movement = BirthOnlyMovement(kernel, NoBoundary())\n\n    traits = GaussTrait(opts, vars)\n    native = fill(true, numSpecies)\n    abun = rand(Multinomial(individuals, numSpecies))\n    sppl = SpeciesList(numSpecies, traits, abun, resource_vec,\n        movement, param, native)\n    nichefit = Gauss{typeof(first(opts))}()\n    eco = Ecosystem(sppl, habitat, nichefit)\n    simulate!(eco, times, timestep)\n    endabuns[i] = sum(eco.abundances.matrix)\nend\n\nbar!(string.(areas), endabuns, grid = false, xlab = \"Area (km²)\",\nylab = \"Total abundance\", guidefontsize = 16,\ntickfontsize= 16, titlefontsize=24, margin = 10.0*Plots.mm,\nlabel = \"\", subplot = 3, title = \"C\", titleloc = :left,\nleft_margin = 20.0 *Plots.mm)\n\n## Sustain large number of species ##\ntimes = 10years; timestep = 1month\nlensim = length(0month:timestep:times)\nreps = 10\nspecies = [100, 500, 1_000, 5_000]\nSR = zeros(Float64, length(species), reps)\nfor r in 1:reps\n    for i in eachindex(species)\n        numSpecies = species[i]; grd = (10,10); demand=(450000.0kJ/m^2, 192.0nm/m^2);\n        individuals = 100_000_000; area = 100.0km^2;\n        totalK = (4.5e11kJ/km^2, 192.0mm/km^2)\n\n        habitat1 = simplehabitat(298.0K, grd, totalK[1], area)\n        habitat2 = simplehabitat(298.0K, grd, totalK[2], area)\n        supply = SupplyCollection2(habitat1.supply, habitat2.supply)\n        habitat = GridHabitat{typeof(habitat1.regime), typeof(supply)}(habitat1.regime, habitat1.active, supply, habitat1.names)\n\n        vars = rand(Uniform(1.0, 5.0), numSpecies) .* K\n        opts = 298.0K .+ vars .* range(-3, stop = 3, length = numSpecies)\n        av_dist = rand(Uniform(0.6, 2.4), numSpecies) .* km\n        kernel = GaussianKernel.(av_dist, 10e-10)\n\n        death = abs.(rand(Normal(0.15, 0.135), numSpecies)) ./year\n        birth = death\n        l = 1.0\n        s = 0.1\n        boost = 1.0\n\n        size_mean = rand(Normal(1.0, 0.5), numSpecies) .* m^2\n        # Set up how much energy each species consumes\n        resource_vec1 = SolarDemand(abs.(demand[1] .* size_mean))\n        resource_vec2 = WaterDemand(abs.(demand[2] .* size_mean))\n\n        resource_vec = DemandCollection2(resource_vec1, resource_vec2)\n        param = PopGrowth{typeof(unit(birth[1]))}(birth, death, l, s , boost)\n\n        # Create ecosystem\n\n        movement = BirthOnlyMovement(kernel, NoBoundary())\n\n        traits = GaussTrait(opts, vars)\n        native = fill(true, numSpecies)\n        abun = rand(Multinomial(individuals, numSpecies))\n        sppl = SpeciesList(numSpecies, traits, abun, resource_vec,\n            movement, param, native)\n        nichefit = Gauss{typeof(first(opts))}()\n        eco = Ecosystem(sppl, habitat, nichefit)\n        simulate!(eco, times, timestep)\n        SR[i, r] = sum(sum(eco.abundances.matrix, dims = 2) .> 0)\n        print(\".\")\n    end\nend\n\nmeanSR = dropdims(mean(SR, dims = 2), dims = 2)\nsdSR = dropdims(std(SR, dims = 2), dims = 2)\n\nbar!(string.(species), meanSR ./species, yerr= sdSR ./ species, grid = false, xlab = \"Number of species introduced\",\nylab = \"% Species survived\", guidefontsize = 16,\ntickfontsize= 16, titlefontsize=24, margin = 10.0*Plots.mm,\nlabel = \"\",  title = \"D\", subplot = 4, titleloc = :left,\nleft_margin = 20.0 *Plots.mm, ylim = (0, 1))\n\n(Image: ) Model testing on island ecosystems. (A) Total abundance of 100 species, with varying resources of water and solar energy across the grid. (B) Total abundance of 100 species, with increasing area size. (C) Total abundance of 100 species, with increasing grid square resolution. (D) Percentage of species survived after 10 years of simulation.","title":"2. Varying resources, grid sizes, areas and number of species"},{"category":"section","location":"examples/#3.-Dispersal","page":"Examples","text":"Finally, we verify that dispersal is functioning as expected. This figure shows the overall abundance of an island populated with two species at opposite extremes of the ecosystem after ten years of simulation. The species moved faster and further into the unpopulated island centre when they had higher average dispersal distances, though again with some edge effects.\n\ntimes = 50years; timestep = 1month\nlensim = length(0month:timestep:times)\ndistances = [0.5, 1.0, 2.0, 4.0]\nendabuns = zeros(Int64, 10, 10, length(distances))\nfor i in eachindex(distances)\n    numSpecies = 2; grd = (10,10); demand=(450000.0kJ/m^2, 192.0nm/m^2);\n    individuals = 0; area = 100.0km^2;\n    totalK = (4.5e11kJ/km^2, 192.0mm/km^2)\n\n    habitat1 = simplehabitat(298.0K, grd, totalK[1], area)\n    habitat2 = simplehabitat(298.0K, grd, totalK[2], area)\n    supply = SupplyCollection2(habitat1.supply, habitat2.supply)\n    habitat = GridHabitat{typeof(habitat1.regime), typeof(supply)}(habitat1.regime, habitat1.active, supply, habitat1.names)\n\n    vars = fill(2.0, numSpecies) .* K\n    opts = fill(298.0, numSpecies) .* K\n    av_dist = fill(distances[i], numSpecies) .* km\n    kernel = GaussianKernel.(av_dist, 10e-10)\n\n    death = 0.15/ year\n    birth = death\n    l = 1.0\n    s = 0.1\n    boost = 1.0\n\n    size_mean = 1.0m^2\n    # Set up how much energy each species consumes\n    resource_vec1 = SolarDemand(fill(demand[1] * size_mean, numSpecies))\n    resource_vec2 = WaterDemand(fill(demand[2] * size_mean, numSpecies))\n\n    resource_vec = DemandCollection2(resource_vec1, resource_vec2)\n    param = EqualPop(birth, death, l, s , boost)\n\n    # Create ecosystem\n\n    movement = BirthOnlyMovement(kernel, NoBoundary())\n\n    traits = GaussTrait(opts, vars)\n    native = fill(true, numSpecies)\n    abun = rand(Multinomial(individuals, numSpecies))\n    sppl = SpeciesList(numSpecies, traits, abun, resource_vec,\n        movement, param, native)\n    nichefit = Gauss{typeof(first(opts))}()\n    eco = Ecosystem(sppl, habitat, nichefit)\n    eco.abundances.grid[1, :, 1] .= 100.0\n    eco.abundances.grid[2, :, 10] .= 100.0\n    simulate!(eco, times, timestep)\n    endabuns[:, :, i] = sum(eco.abundances.matrix, dims = 1)\nend\n\nheatmap(grid = false, xlab = \"Distance (km)\",\nylab = \"Distance (km)\", size = (1200, 800),\nguidefontsize = 12,tickfontsize= 12, titlefontsize=18,\nmargin = 10.0*Plots.mm, legendfontsize = 12, label = \"\",\nlayout = (@layout [a b; c d]), link = :both)\ntitles = [\"A\", \"B\", \"C\", \"D\"]\nfor i in 1:4\n    m = distances[i]\n    display(heatmap!(1:10,1:10, endabuns[:, :, i],\n    grid = false, xlab = \"Distance (km)\", ylab = \"Distance (km)\",\n    guidefontsize = 16, tickfontsize= 16,\n    titlefontsize=24, title = titles[i], margin = 10.0*Plots.mm,\n    label = \"\", subplot = i, titleloc = :left,\n    clim = (0, 1.5e4), link = :both))\nend\n\n(Image: ) Total abundance of two species in island ecosystems after 10 years of simulation, with species populated at opposite sides of the island. Those with higher dispersal distances moved further away from their starting populations at a faster rate. (A) Mean dispersal distance of 0.5km, (B) mean dispersal distance of 1km, (C) Mean dispersal distance of 2km, Mean dispersal distance of 4km.","title":"3. Dispersal"},{"category":"section","location":"basics/#The-basics-of-EcoSISTEM.jl","page":"Basics","text":"","title":"The basics of EcoSISTEM.jl"},{"category":"section","location":"basics/#Install","page":"Basics","text":"using Pkg\nPkg.add(\"EcoSISTEM\")","title":"Install"},{"category":"section","location":"basics/#Setting-up-an-ecosystem","page":"Basics","text":"The package runs on an Ecosystem containing information about species, the SpeciesList, their environment, Habitat and the nichefit between the two, AbstractNicheFit.","title":"Setting up an ecosystem"},{"category":"section","location":"basics/#A-simple-example","page":"Basics","text":"Load required packages\n\nusing EcoSISTEM\nusing EcoSISTEM.Units\nusing Unitful, Unitful.DefaultSymbols\nusing Distributions\nusing Diversity\n\nSet up initial parameters for ecosystem\n\nnumSpecies = 10; grid = (5, 5); demand= 10.0kJ; individuals=1000; area = 1000.0*km^2; totalK = 1.0kJ/km^2\n\nSet up how much energy each species consumes\n\nresource_vec = SolarDemand(fill(demand, numSpecies))\n\nSet rates for birth and death\n\nbirth = 0.6/year\ndeath = 0.6/year\nlongevity = 1.0\nsurvival = 0.2\nboost = 1.0\n# Collect model parameters together\nparam = EqualPop(birth, death, longevity, survival, boost)\n\nCreate kernel for movement\n\nkernel = fill(GaussianKernel(10.0km, 10e-10), numSpecies)\nmovement = BirthOnlyMovement(kernel, Torus())\n\nCreate species list, including their temperature preferences, seed abundance and native status\n\nopts = fill(274.0K, numSpecies)\nvars = fill(0.5K, numSpecies)\ntraits = GaussTrait(opts, vars)\nnative = fill(true, numSpecies)\n# abun = rand(Multinomial(individuals, numSpecies))\nabun = fill(div(individuals, numSpecies), numSpecies)\nsppl = SpeciesList(numSpecies, traits, abun, resource_vec,\n    movement, param, native)\n\nCreate abiotic environment - even grid of one temperature\n\nhabitat = simplehabitat(274.0K, grid, totalK, area)\n\nSet nichefit between species and environment (gaussian)\n\nnichefit = Gauss{typeof(1.0K)}()\n\nCreate ecosystem\n\neco = Ecosystem(sppl, habitat, nichefit)\n\nRun simulation\n\n# EcoSISTEM Parameters\nburnin = 5years; times = 50years; timestep = 1month; record_interval = 3months; repeats = 1\nlensim = length(0years:record_interval:times)\n# Burnin\n@time simulate!(eco, burnin, timestep)\n\nPlot using SpatialEcology\n\nusing SpatialEcology\nplot(eco)","title":"A simple example"},{"category":"section","location":"#EcoSISTEM.jl","page":"Home","text":"EcoSISTEM is a Julia package that provides functionality for simulating species undergoing dynamic biological processes such as birth, death, competition and dispersal, as well as environmental changes in climate and habitat.\n\nThe package was primarily developed for global scale simulations of plant biodiversity. The underlying model for this is described in the arXiv paper arXiv:1911.12257 (q-bio.QM) Dynamic virtual ecosystems as a tool for detecting large-scale responses of biodiversity to environmental and land-use change.\n\nThere are substantial changes to the package introduced through the dev branch (docs), including epidemiological simulations and refactoring of the code base for further flexibility.\n\nThis package is in beta now, so please raise an issue if you find any problems. For more information on how to contribute, please read our contributing guidelines.\n\n(Image: )","title":"EcoSISTEM.jl"},{"category":"section","location":"simulation-jl/#Table-of-datasets-currently-in-use-by-EcoSISTEM.jl","page":"Table of datasets currently in use by EcoSISTEM.jl","text":"Preliminary list of parameters/datasets.\n\nName of parameter/ dataset Description Value Source Other info (e.g. stability)\np_s Probability of developing symptoms 0.96 (From Thibaud's original model) \np_h Probability of hospitalisation 0.2 Guess \ncfr_home Case fatality ratio (at home) 0.1 Guess \ncfr_hospital Case fatality ratio (at hospital) 0.1 Guess \nT_lat Latent period 5 days (From Thibaud's original model) \nT_asym Asymptomatic period 3 days (From Thibaud's original model) \nT_sym Symptomatic period 5 days (From Thibaud's original model) \nT_hosp Hospitalisation period 5 days (From Thibaud's original model) \nT_rec Recovery period 11 days (From Thibaud's original model) \nmu_1 Probability of becoming Asymptomatic 1/T_lat  \nmu_2 Probability of becoming Symptomatic ps * 1/Tasym  \nhospitalisation Probability of becoming Hospitalised ph * 1/Tsym  \nsigma_1 Probability of Recovery from Asymptomatic (1 - ps) * 1/Tasym  \nsigma_2 Probability of Recovery from Symptomatic (1 - ph)*(1 - cfrhome)*1/T_rec  \nsigma_hospital Probability of Recovery from Hospital (1 - cfrhosp) * 1/Thosp  \ndeath_home Probability of Death at home cfrhome * 2/Thosp  \ndeath_hospital Probability of Death at hospital cfrhosp * 1/Thosp  \nScotlandDensity2011 Scottish population density at 1km grid  UK census 2011 - A Reeves 'Covid19-ScottishCensusData' repo \ndispersal_dist Average dispersal distance of virus per disease category 2.0km per infectious disease category Guess Varies depending on grid size\nmean_pref Mean temperature preference of virus 298K Guess Currently tuned to fit environment perfectly\nvar_pref Temperature niche width of virus 0.1K Guess Currently tuned to fit environment perfectly\nbirth Probability of giving birth per individual 1.3e-4/day (20-40 year olds), 0 otherwise Guess \ndeath Probability of giving natural mortality per individual 2.7e-5/day Guess \nvirusgrowthasymp Rate of generating virus per asymptomatic individual 0.1/day Guess \nvirusgrowthsymp Rate of generating virus per symptomatic individual 0.1/day Guess \nbeta_force Force of infection 10.0/day Guess \nbeta_env Environmental transmission 10.0/day Guess ","title":"Table of datasets currently in use by EcoSISTEM.jl"}]
}
